The parliament did not support an amendment to liberate Tymoshenko
Ukraine's parliament today rejected the proposal to repeal the amendment of the section of the Criminal Code condemning the opposition leader Yulia Tymoshenko.
The amendment would open the door to the release of the expression minister, but parliamentarians rejected the proposal to reduce the penalties for economic crimes in the second reading.
In October, Tymoshenko was sentenced to seven years in prison for the alleged signing of an agreement with Russia disadvantageous for Ukraine on purchase of natural gas.
The ruling is not yet firm, the court of appeal has an obligation to review it in December.
Tymoshenko was convinced that it was a political revenge of the regime, and even in the West have raised doubts about the impartiality of the court.
The proposal to withdraw paragraph 365 of the Criminal Code which condemned the former prime minister was supported by 147 Members in the vote.
For approval is required 226 votes.
