Begins a new era of the crisis
France and the rest of Europe are hunting of the search engine of investors
Statistical a whirlwind has spread through Europe
Individual states have published their data for Q3 GDP.
The Czech economy in the period intercuatrimestral has stagnated, while France and Germany have grown.
However, the bond market today has broken records.
Investors are no longer set only in Italy, but also in Spain, France, Austria and others.
The statistical offices of the eurozone, Germany, the Czech Republic and other European countries, have already published its preliminary estimates on economic growth in the third quarter.
Germany's GDP grew by 0.5 percent expected, France 0.4%
Both countries have made public the data for the second quarter, Germany has improved more than expected (growth of 0.3% instead of the expected 0.1%), while in France it gave a slight decrease of 0.1% (the original data spoke of stagnation).
The Czech economy grew interanualmente 1.5% in the third quarter of this year.
However, in the period intercuatrimestral, gross domestic product (GDP) has stagnated and according to the ČSÚ settles the trend towards the gradual slowdown in the growth of economic development.
The results are even worse than the forecasts of analysts.
Main events:
Interanualmente, the Czech economy grew in the third quarter of this year, 1.5%, but quarterly has stagnated.
In the third quarter, the German economy, according to preliminary data and recalculated seasonally, grew by 0.5%.
The economy of the euro zone and the European Union, between July and September, compared with the previous quarter, rose 0.2%, which is in line with the expectations of analysts.
The Greek economy has fallen interanualmente 5.2%.
The interest of its 10-year bonds is 28.45%.
The interest of Italian and Spanish bonds has grown to critical limits.
The problematic situation starts to also affect Austria, the Netherlands, France, Belgium, etc.
The interests of the ten-year bonds remain at 4 percent, while in the area, the situation is getting worse.
In Germany are being raised voices saying that the ECB should grant loans ultimately.
