How have evolved the prices of travel since 1989
Until 1989 in the then Czechoslovakia had only five state travel agencies authorized: Čedok, Sporturist, CKM, Rekrea and Autoturist.
Travel agencies of the time sold in most cases only travel to the socialist bloc, then travel to the West were very restricted.
Czech tourists were, therefore, on holiday to the beaches of the GDR (German Democratic Republic), the Soviet Union, in Crimea in the Black Sea to Bulgaria and Romania (both in the Black Sea) and Hungary (Balaton).
A positive exception was the period between 1962 and 1972, when you could travel to Yugoslavia, however, after the Yugoslav regime tipped towards the west and travel to the Czech tourists were then fairly restricted.
A great paradox of socialism was the fact that the citizens of the socialist bloc (i.e., also the Checoeslovacos) are not allowed to travel freely and individually or even by the socialist countries.
If a citizen wanted to travel individually, for example, Poland and the Soviet Union, needed a letter of invitation, if not, the individual travel was not possible.
Travel agencies in those days will also travel to the West, but one was put in the queue with a sleeping bag and spend it all night, or have "well known" in the agency.
Still not everything was won.
The so-called "promise of change" that was the condition for travel to the West, is not attached to the "people politically unreliable," that they could not travel at all.
The Czechoslovak currency was not a freely convertible currency and, without a guarantee of change, it was not possible to obtain resources (the West) to travel to the West.
The vast majority of Czechs spent their holidays in their own country, so we had a large number of huts and houses of summer, that the Czechs grew. This habit still persists.
The way to travel from the Czechs has suffered since 1989 a real revolution.
While until 1989 for us was not going over the holiday in the GDR or Bulgaria, last year the Czechs did 4.5 million holiday trips to countries around the world.
Is nna great paradox, which today because we are not aware of the fact that the current favorite destination, Croatia, until 1989 could not travel freely, because it was part of the then Yugoslavia.
At the beginning of the 1990s was imposed the exemption of visas to travel to the neighbouring states of Western Europe, which caused a huge wave of short-term visits, especially in Vienna or Germany.
The checoeslovacos, for a long time, there were sick of the excursions to the West, everyone wanted to see at least for a time.
For example, slept in Paris groups of Czechs in parks in tents, because our income then we were not allowed to pay for a hotel or pension.
A typical feature of the Czechs at that time was carried with them (canned food, sausages, etc.) to save.
Another important moment was the introduction of the convertibility of the Czech koruna, so our tourists could finally, after decades, buy freely Western currency.
Our standard of living and with him also increased average wages, what about 1997 led to an increase in demand for travel.
With the increase in demand for travel agencies began, from 1997 onwards regularly, to prepare for journeys using the connections of charter flights, which was incredibly lower fares in comparison with the past, thanks to the possibility of obtaining discounts for the volume of passengers.
At the end of the 90 of the last century, because the Czechs travelling without a visa to almost all developed countries, except the US, which further simplified our trips.
Another interesting time in the history of tourism post-revolutionary happened back in 2000, when it was organised, thanks to a huge demand, the first direct flight from the Czech Republic to a country exotic, and went to Thailand.
Since that year, are all those years direct charter flights with Czech tourists was distant countries and warm. This winter is already fly directly from the Czech Republic to 12 exotic destinations.
Exotic countries currently visiting the nearly 100 thousand Czechs per year.
Another interesting time of this era, which symbolises our development post-revolutionary, came in 2008.
On 17 November 2008, the US removed visas for Czech tourists, with what our country went to be among the world's most developed countries.
In 2008, Czechs, for the first time in its history, have spent more than half of their holidays abroad (50.3%) and for the first time in its history, have been spent on trips abroad more than 15 billion Koruny per head, including expenditure in the place of residence.
Ordinary General Assembly convened to elect the president, which could end up again in deadlock.
For nearly five months without Czech football is chairman and it is likely that the successor of Ivan Hašek as President of the Czech Federation of Soccer (FAČR), will not be known or after the convening of the next General Assembly meeting that will take place this Thursday in Nymburk.
In fact, it has not yet reached an agreement on the voting rules to follow.
Without them, will not even vote to choose between the three candidates.
Stakeholders to chair the Czech football are Jindřich Rajchl, Miroslav Pelta and Tomáš Paclík.
Hašek resigned in June, but not before convening his colleagues with the aim of finding a strong person who knew the football in the future.
However, after the conclusion of the era Hašek, triggered a dispute between the two federations of partnership unable to reach an agreement to choose a candidate.
This was in evidence on 16 September when he had to be elected the new president.
General Assembly delegates gathered in vain in the National House (Národní dům), located in the district of Smíchov praguense, because the talks had been blocked and not only in terms of the method of choice.
No consensus was reached or in terms of who in the General Assembly had a right to vote - only the legal representatives or delegates with full powers.
From that moment, and because of this single point, there was a partial agreement, backed by the recommendation of the Institute of State and Law, according to which the representation for full powers is not possible.
However, disputes over the electoral code remain open.
More light on the situation could not shed or the Executive Board, at its meetings, regular or extraordinary, basically did not solve anything.
The opinion on the possibility of vote has changed a couple of times already, but the worst point remains the same.
The question is: How to proceed in the third round to avoid the deadlock?
"The dispute revolves around whether to proceed in accordance with the statutes or find another model," says Dušan Svoboda, one of the three vice-presidents of the FAČR, which, from the direction of the association, which represents professional football.
According to the model proposed in the statutes, in the third round win the candidate who has a higher percentage of support in the federation to which will present his candidacy.
The Region of Moravia is willing to reach a compromise so that it can win the candidate with a higher percentage of total votes in both federations.
The Bohemian, however, under the condition that the winner, according to these calculations percentage should have the majority of at least two-thirds.
"It would, however, the connection to the two previous rounds and completely negate the concept of a bicameral system," as Svoboda understands the objections of the Morava, according to which it would be better not to touch the order and vote according to the applicable statutes.
With this, surprisingly, agrees also Tomaš Paclík, even if it means that the electoral rules laid down by the Statute of all candidates should be more Pelta.
"I would like to be voted the most in accordance with the statutes."
"Not to invent any nonsense about representatives at the last General Assembly," says the owner of Victoria Plzen, who is running for the first time as a candidate and that his comments directed mainly against Pelta.
Pelta remains optimistic.
According to him, in Nymburk will decide on the new president and he believes that the candidates in the future to cooperate constructively.
"All the passions are apaciguarán with the party today of our national team at the European Championship.
"Football will be a major player, and cooperate more at ease," says the representative of Jablonice, which of the three candidates has more experience in management of football, both professional and regional level.
Rajchl is the more reticent.
"I hope that an agreement is reached, but, unfortunately, the situation is much more complicated."
"This is not about the conflict between Bohemian and Moravian, but there are attempts to adjust the rules to their own convenience."
"This may result in a new blockade of the General Assembly."
"Anyway, I hope that common sense will prevail," said Rajchl.
Because there is not much time for all parties to reach an agreement.
Some negotiations had to be made in Montenegro, but who can know until we start the party if the football team will be complete?
The special plane, which had to travel to Podgorica, among other vice-presidents Dalibor Kucera and Rajchl, has not emerged this morning by technical problems in Prague, having to find an alternative to transport to the executive committee will take place at the place where the party of classification.
Perhaps the decisive meeting, finally, it could be that will take place at ministerial level, which, according to be held this Wednesday.
Josef Dobeš, Minister of Education, Youth and Sports, I would very much like to incorporate the parties divided the country's most powerful sports organization to reach an agreement.
There is a lot at stake: State subsidies, the credibility of football and also the next General Assembly of the Central Committee of the Czechoslovak federation of sport (ČSTV) that will try to give a new direction to the Czech sport after the financial problems of the house of Sazka lotteries.
