Personal level massacre
The intense and generous new book by Peter Englund, The beauty and the pain of the battle (The Beauty and the Sorrow: An intimate story of the First World War, "begins with a long dramatis personae of the kind that can make one falls the soul to their feet.
Here are some tips for action: Start mildly this page and make it a their brand pages.
It will be very familiar with these people in the narrative novelística of Mr Englund, and this dramatis personae will work as their GPS, a beacon for those few moments in which, as one of his men and women, is confused and helpless in the fog of war.
Mr Englund is a historian and journalist.
It is also the new permanent secretary of the Swedish Academy, which awards the Nobel Prize for Literature.
What he has written here is an unusual book, which describes, rightly, as "a work of anti-story."
Contains some notable names, treated important or famous battles; there are virtually no ambassadors, elegant journalists or discussions about tactics or material.
It is not so much a book about what happened, explains, "a book about how it happened." Is about "feelings, impressions, experiences and states of humor."
"The beauty and the pain of the battle" combines the experiences in times of war of more or less ordinary men and women 20, on both sides of the war, from schoolchildren and Gardens to escaladores, doctors, ambulance drivers and administrative.
Some of these people will become heroes.
Some become prisoners of war, or lose its members, will become crazy or die.
Their lives parpadean here as votivas candles lit in a church; new ones are added to the mix, while others turn off lights.
The book by Mr Englund is a departure from the standard history books.
It is also a corrective to the notion that the First World War, was the only fatal trench warfare on the western front.
"The beauty and the pain of the battle" moves of expertly through other theatres of war: The Alps, the Balkans, the eastern front, Mesopotamia, eastern Africa.
Soldiers in this book I fall over the hives; one spends Christmas in Egypt under the pyramids; the flies fly-fly are an intractable problem.
This is a book moving, almost from the start.
The war is swamping the lives of these people as a natural disaster, a Hurricane Katrina that reeks of cordita.
When the artillery fire was heard in the distance, and you're a woman who is at home with your children, are there or huyes?
Anyway, who comes?
Almost nobody understands what is happening, or even why it has to fight this war.
"Lack of facts," observes Mr Englund, "has been filled with speculation, assumptions, hopes, fears, fixed ideas, conspiracy theories, dreams and nightmares and rumors."
"The beauty and the pain of the battle" continues to individuals as Florence Farmborough, an English nurse in the Russian army, and Richard Stumpf, a young German sailor of the fleet of the high seas.
Their stories have been mostly of memoirs, letters and other material already published earlier.
Explanations of their lives can be frightening or moving, but are more full of life in the accumulation of small moments, details lost, Mr Englund.
Many of these are about deprivation and make do with what we have.
About tell the story of a German schoolgirl says: "Substitutes, substitutes for all parties."
"Ersatz coffee, aluminium false, imitation rubber, paper masks, wooden buttons."
Still talking about the food substitute in Germany.
Describes "meat made from rice cooked and rolling carnero fat (and topped off with a bone false made of wood); tobacco fact roots and peladuras of potatoes dry; shoes with soles of wood."
There is, observes, "837 permitted substitutes for meat in the production of sausages, 511 coffee substitutes registered."
Some stories are about the honor and courage.
An American acknowledges its own momentum towards the savagery and says about the war: "Sientes that, after all, this is what men are designed and not to sit in chairs with a cigarette and a whiskey, the newspaper of the afternoon or a bestseller, and pretend that the veneer of civilisation and means that there is a barbaric behind this pechera almidonada and tachonada."
Instead a British soldier realises that probably will die, and that no one will notice or care.
"Once you are resigned to the thought of sacrificed, you would think that could happen in front of the public," he writes.
Instead, it is horribly similar "to a convicted being strangled in secret."
Other observations are about an old Europe disappearing, and about new types of terror.
"The conflict has increasingly become an economic competition," writes Mr Englund, "a war between factories."
It reflects the arrival of what he calls "a new species in the bestiario of the young century: The mass murderer eloquent and convinced ideologically with good clothes of clothing that executes its carnage while is sitting behind a desk."
People behave in unforeseen ways; there are both ignoble behaviour as heroic.
Mr Englund speaks of the soldiers who tried to actively take a venereal disease of prostitutes as a way of evading the service in the front.
"The most grotesque expression of this can be seen trade gonocócico., soldiers and buy embadurnan with their genitals with the hope of ending up in the hospital," he writes.
"Those who are truly desperate looking it over their eyes, which often leads to a lifetime blindness."
In this translation of the Swede made by Peter Grave, the prose of Mr Englund agile but not extravagant, is perfectly suited to the task.
In dozens of small scenes reflects the way in which the war to "exceptionally uncontrollable forces unleashed: Extreme nationalism, social revolution, religious hatred."
People start to ask why their leaders are doing to combat them.
The best books about World War I have often been indirect, such as The Great War and Modern Memory of Paul Fussell, or novels as Without novelty in the face of Erich Maria highlight, rather than comprehensive stories.
The volume of Mr Englund joins a pantheon unconventional.
His book is one of the most devastating end that I can remember in a work of non-fiction.
Not will reveal.
But it is as if it had come from his book, torn between your fingers of this page dramatis personae, and had burned with a match.
