The workers' union will require support to the city by redundancies
The union that represents hundreds of school support workers who lost their jobs last month plans to sue the city on Wednesday, claiming that the redundancies were unnecessary and discriminatory because of their disproportionate impact on schools that serve poor students.
Demand is, perhaps, the ultimate weapon available to the union, the municipal district 37, in their effort to repeal the redundancies.
Six hundred and seventy-two assistants from school, the coordinators of parents and other employees who were among the worst paid the city lost its work on 7 October, in a move that the union leaders have described as a political vendetta for his refusal to allow the spring, access on the part of the city to a health care fund in charge of working groups to close its budget gap.
Municipal authorities have strongly denied that accusation.
At a hearing in the city last month, the education adviser, Dennis M. Walcott, said that the redundancies were part of the budget approved in June.
A member of the Council contraatacó saying that nothing in the budget specified that the members of the school support staff would be made redundant.
The 37 municipal district officials said they filed the complaint in writing, warning to the Department of Education that would be sued and held a press conference Wednesday to announce the official presentation of the demand, in State Supreme Court in Manhattan.
Demand will include Mr Walcott and the Department of Education of the city as defendants, and has eight workers made redundant as plaintiffs, all of them black or Latino, like most of the assistants who lost their jobs.
Elizabeth Thomas, spokesman of the Legal Department of the city, said that the city had not seen the lawsuit and therefore could not comment on the specific allegations.
According to a draft of the demand obtained by The New York Times, the union has focused on the number of layoffs at schools in poor areas of the city to support a claim for unfair treatment, saying that poor schools lost more assistants, as it had been subsidized chronically underfunded.
It Noted that while there was no redundancies in Staten Island and a few redundancies in schools on the Upper East Side or TriBeCa, 17 school workers lost their jobs in the District 23 in Brownsville, Brooklyn, and 46 were fired in Districts 8 and 9 in the South Bronx.
Taking into account the loss of five of the eight assistants employed by the Public School 36 in Harlem, where the 68 percent of students live in poverty, the complaint says, "This is not a district of wealthy parents who can raise funds to cover the budget deficit."
The district's budget P.D. 36 fell 3.26 percent this year, and also lost money when the city has changed the way it calculates the additional funding for each student enrolment for poor in schools.
The union also states that the directors of secondary schools may have been deceived by the language in a memorandum authorizing the dismissal of the coordinators of parents.
The memorandum used the word "surplus" to describe the action, despite the fact that "surplus" describes more often the act of moving to a master of the payroll of a school in a bag of work, whose salaries are paid by the central office.
"Sixty-six coordinators of parents were made redundant," says the draft of the complaint, "and not only in surplus."
Mission completed, Congress prepared to reach an agreement on Libya
It seems that Republicans and Democrats on Capitol Hill are willing to agree on anything related to the uprising in Libya.
All that was needed was that the rebellion had success, that the veteran dictator Muammar Gaddafi was captured and killed and the participation of the United States came to an end.
Tuesday, the Senate Foreign Relations Committee will consider a resolution, sponsored by the chairman John Kerry (Democrat from Massachusetts), along with Senators John McCain, Republican of Arizona) and Joseph I. Lieberman, independent of Connecticut, applauding Libyans for his successful rebellion and US troops for their "courage".
"This resolution is to honour the brave people of Libya, to begin to rebuild their country," said Kerry.
"It is an affirmation of bipartisan support for their democratic aspirations."
The language may seem harmless, but nothing on the debate on Libya has been easy so far.
This summer, lawmakers of both parties fought among themselves and with the White House over the wording of a number of resolutions to approve or reject the role of the US military in the NATO mission in Libya.
In June, Kerry and McCain submitted a resolution authorizing the limited use of US military forces in Libya.
The bill was defeated in the House by a wide margin bipartisan, and never came to be voted on in the Senate.
But on the same day that the bill was rejected in the House, the House also rejected a measure that would have cut funds for US operations in Libya.
That left the US mission in a kind of purgatory of legislation - with Congress sufficiently troublesome as to criticize the handling by Obama of the mission, but not so angry enough to actually mow the grass under his feet.
Then, the indecision of Congress was overtaken by events.
Tripoli fell into the hands of the Libyan rebels in August, and Gaddafi was killed on 20 October.
The NATO mission officially ended on 31 October.
Now the Senate could be ready to act.
The resolution of the Committee on Foreign Affairs "congratulates the people of Libya for his tremendous courage and remarkable resilience to free themselves" and "pays tribute to the men and women of the Armed Forces of the United States and its coalition partners who participated in military operations to protect the people of Libya for their extraordinary courage and professionalism."
The resolution also "declares the national interest of the United States in a successful and irreversible transition to democracy in Libya."
Ganará does the new measure the full support of the Committee on Foreign Affairs, or divided lawmakers as it did the bill June?
The latest version was rejected by Senator Richard G. Lugar (Indiana), the top Republican on the committee.
The spokesman of Venue said on Monday that he had not yet seen the final version of the new bill.
On the other side of the Capitol, the House will vote this week on a constitutional amendment requiring a balanced budget, a legislative priority for almost all the Congressional Republicans and some Democrats.
The measure, sponsored by the Republican Bob Goodlatte of Virginia (Republican), will be the first constitutional amendment on the budget or any other issue that achieves a vote by the entire assembly in the House or the Senate in this Congress.
Other legislators have not succeeded so far to get their amendments to the assembly, but not for lack of trying.
The Goodlatte is just one of the 68 constitutional amendments that have been introduced in this Congress, covering a wide range of issues.
Some are duplicated - the same bill proposes in both the House and the Senate - and others with slight variations among themselves.
There are at least 15 versions of the balanced budget Amendment only in the House, and another handful that "will control federal spending."
Some of these projects bills also are identical among themselves, but they give their sponsors - especially novice Republicans seeking to refine their resumes - the opportunity to boast that they were the "authors" of such a measure.
The Budget Control Act, which was passed in August, required that both the House and the Senate vote an amendment to the budget balance.
In March, 58 senators voted in favour of a non-binding resolution that supports the idea that amendment.
Beyond the budget, several members want to limit the number of mandates that members of Congress can meet, while the Democratic representative José E. Serrano (in New York), wants to take the two-term limit for presidents.
The representative Jesse L. Jackson Jr. (Christian by Illinois) has proposed a series of amendments which guarantee the right to a quality education and health care, among other issues.
An amendment banning gay marriage is a perennial proposal, as well as one that prohibits the burning of flags.
Some legislators also want to allow the cancellation of federal laws if they are rejected by two-thirds of the states.
So enthusiasts who have been members to propose amendments, there are moving at a faster pace than in previous years.
In the 111th Congress, lawmakers proposed 77 changes, and 66 in the 110th.
The pace is unacceptable in comparison with that of the 1990s, when members regularly presented more than 150 amendments every two years, according to figures provided by the Library of the Senate.
But not had much more success then than they are now.
The last amendment added - 27 - was ratified in 1992, but in fact it was proposed by Congress in 1789.
