Troops felt more pity that respect
The event was a display of Wall Street that raised millions of dollars for homeless veterans in New York.
Kid Rock sang a Ballad about the impotence, frustration and loss.
At that time, several hundred soldiers, sailors, airmen and marines stormed their posts around him.
The crowd of label got up and applauded.
"The men and women were seen as heroes," said David Saltzman, who organized the fundraising of spring.
A senior military officer in the display, also known as the then chairman of the Joint Chiefs of Staff, Admiral Mike Mullen, saw the role of troops in a different way.
"The showed as a kind of orphaned children," the officer wrote in an e-mail.
I am sure that the organizers had good intentions.
That they had.
But it was not respect, really. It was unfortunate.
The conflicting views starkly illustrate the difficult relationship that has taken hold of the military and an American public often distant, sometimes adorador.
Troops are lavished with praise for their sacrifices.
But the praise has a price, say members of the service.
The public increasingly acts as if he were death those in uniform.
"We are not victims at all," said Brigadier General Sean B. MacFarland, who commanded troops in Iraq and Afghanistan will soon towards.
"But it seems that the only way that some show their support is set to us in the role of souls helpless."
The issue is a very sensitive issue for the military leaders, who do not want to seem ungrateful or disagree with the public they serve.
Also realize that anger faced by troops who returned in recent years of the Vietnam War was much worse.
As a result, the majority of the talks on the pity are carried out in silence and in private between war veterans.
After his two sons returned to combat with the Marine Corps, Colonel withdrawn Mark Cancian warned that people apart from the military would consider its service from two perspectives.
Some would regard them with a sense of fear because it clashed with insurgents and travelled to exotic places.
Others wonder whether there would be a "veteran angry and violent beneath the surface," said Cancian, who fought in Iraq and returned to a high level of government in Washington.
During their search for employment, he said, felt that some interviewers subtly had asked whether it would be able to endure under the pressure of a demanding work of Washington immediately after his tour of combat.
"When you talk about your service, you need to address the negative impressions," recalled Cancian contándoselo to their children.
The military concern stems, in part, of the American indifference toward the wars.
The achievements in the field of battle are rarely elected to the praise from a country that has little familiarity with the military and sees little direct benefits of the wars in Iraq and Afghanistan.
"We, as a nation, we no longer military heroism in ways that were quite common in the Second World War," said retired Lt. Gen. David Barno, who commanded US troops in Afghanistan.
Instead, the praise of politicians and the public focus largely on the depth of the suffering of a member of the service.
The troops are recognized by the number of tours that have endured, the number of friends who have lost or the extent of their injuries.
The army faces growing pressure to end the violation
This week, a historic hearing will decide whether 28 men and women have a case against the army for its alleged failure to rape.
If not, hundreds of plaintiffs are being organised for the next.
The soldier first Elizabeth Lyman was 25 years and 11 weeks of pregnancy night in which she says she was raped by a colleague.
It was October 2008, and was on his way back to his barracks at the Miramar Air Base, north of San Diego, after dinner with a friend when he met with a colleague who had a package of 12 cans of beer.
He asked if he could join her in her room to take a drink.
"Sounded an alarm signal," Lyman said.
However, the Texas native left aside their concern.
I thought, no, has 19.
"Is of Texas," he says.
"I had listened to my instincts."
A few minutes of entering the room of Lyman, the man approached him from behind, tirándola down and raping her, he argues.
This week, on 18 November, Lyman and 27 other members of the current and former military personnel anxiously await a court decision in a historic trial to be held in Arlington, Virginia, which will decide if the demand that have filed against the former of Defense Robert Gates and his predecessor, Donald Rumsfeld, will go on trial.
The lawsuit alleges that Gates and Rumsfeld failed in the reduction of the widespread violation between the military, in violation of the constitutional rights of the soldiers.
Filed in February by Susan Burke, a lawyer in Washington, D.C., demand was initially to 17 plaintiffs, but grew to 28 in the following months, 25 women and three men, all of them say they were raped or sexually assaulted by their peers, and that the army failed to investigate, prosecute, or provide adequate justice after the alleged assaults.
Burke said that will by the top brass in the army, because the problem starts with them.
"The army is a structure from the top down," he says.
"Who are the people who are in a position to eradicate the culture of reprisals? The high command."
Burke also said that since February, have been in touch with her nearly 400 more survivors, many of whom could be part of future demands.
His strategy: Instead of accumulating all the plaintiffs in this case, putting all our eggs in one basket, so to speak, will present a number of cases, if necessary, to keep up the pressure.
The defence team for the Department of Defense, led by the federal prosecutor Neil MacBride, has tabled a motion to dismiss the case.
The court documents, obtained by Newsweek, detailing the defence strategy, in essence, that the military cannot be sued for current or former soldiers for injuries sustained in the armed forces.
By a judgment of the Supreme Court of 1950 called the Feres Doctrine, the federal government is not responsible for the damage suffered by the staff in active service.
"Damage alleged are part of the military service of the plaintiffs', say the documents.
The Department of Defense refused to comment for this article.
Things have changed since the 1950s.
While women are still officially forbidden to serve in combat, this distinction is only nominal: Modern wars rarely have clear the front lines.
Both in Iraq and in Afghanistan, the teams of women soldiers are playing increasingly important roles, especially to reach local women in war zones.
The result: Between these two wars, 150 women soldiers have died and two-thirds of them in combat situations.
It is time that the army was also modernize, says Burke.
She is not alone in their struggle, and three other demands are in place, in addition to the hook.
At Yale Law School, the Legal Services Clinic for Veteranos is preparing a case against the four main military academies for allegedly promoting an environment misogynistic.
On the other hand, the non-profit organization Vietnam Veterans of America is making a complaint against the army, which focuses on the diagnosis of "personality disorder" allocated to victims of rape in order to give them the high of service -- a common occurrence, according to activists, as Anu Bhagwati of the Women's Action Network in Service, a human rights group.
His group filed a lawsuit in December against the Veterans administration, accusing him of discriminatory practices in the way it handles complaints of benefits for people who claim to have been sexually assaulted in the service.
There have been nine separate bills in Congress by a bipartisan mix of senators and representatives, proposing a series of corrections.
In 2010 was 3,158 sexual assault reported, according to the Office for the Prevention of Sexual Assault Response and the Department of Defense.
However, the attacks are significantly below reported, and by the Pentagon's own estimates, that figure in approximately 13.5 per cent of the estimated 19000 incidents that occurred this year.
The report, published in March, also examines the rates of prosecution: In 2010, a 20 percent of the cases reported in the army was on trial - half that in the civil justice system.
The plaintiffs in the case of Burke, describe their attacks as only the first of a series of trauma.
In the case of Lyman, denounced the alleged violation of the military police less than an hour after it happened.
That night, he says, he was asked to count the details of its violation 11 different times in a crowd of policemen, doctors, and commanders.
She underwent a rape kit, and the blood of his attacker -- a court in its brazo was found in his bed.
Six months later, in April 2009, Lyman attended a hearing before a judge, during which he was asked about who had had sex with her boyfriend on the day of the attack.
Six people testified as witnesses of personality on behalf of the alleged perpetrator, who was eventually acquitted.
"I remember the day when was read out the verdict," Lyman said.
"I thought I was going to go to work, I found myself screaming from the room."
"I put in the psychiatric unit, and when I left, I remember that I said to my commanding officer," That was not his trial. This was my opinion. "
Lyman was ordered to visit a military psychiatrist, who finally diagnosed with a personality disorder, which did not fit for the service.
In January 2010 was excused from service under terms less-than-honorable, which prevents him from receiving any benefit.
As to whether the case presented by Lyman and his fellow demand continues, it is a long shot, said John Turley, a professor of law at the Faculty of Law George Washington.
However, says, "In my opinion, should be able to move forward."
What stands between them and a verdict is this doctrine that has been criticized since it was published for the first time.
I have been a critic of the Feres Doctrine.
The army is decades behind because it does not have the same incentive and deterrence that raises the responsibility.
And he adds: "The odds are heavily against them... but it is important for them to try."
These things only change when the good people is ready to fight.
If the audience is not on his way, Burke, a lawyer for the plaintiffs, will put the queue to its other hundreds of applicants for future cases.
"We are going to continue to fight against the army in this issue until the reform will take place," he says.
"Or until we muramos, what happens first.
The walls have eyes: Researchers are studying how you on Facebook
Before becoming the new face of the extreme right in Europe, Anders Behring Breivik was simply another kind that aireaba its anti-immigration views online.
Monday, Breivik, who admitted to having carried out a massacre in Norway in July, that left 77 dead, faced his first public court hearing.
While Breivik may have acted alone, was far from being only in cyberspace: Had spent most of the time that preceded his attack to her computer, chatting with some of the millions of nationalists who support the right-wing groups in social networks.
After the tragedy of this summer, researchers wanted to know more about these people.
But, how to find them?
Only easy - you have to go into Facebook.
"We realised that it was not so difficult to reach them," says Jamie Bartlett, principal author of a recently published report on the European digital populism in the centre of British studies demos.
The cache of personal information on Facebook is so encyclopaedic says Bartlett, that researchers could simply use the tool of advertising to determine their desired demographic characteristics with a scientific accuracy - the way that sellers have been using for years.
The team of Bartlett found half a million fan of right-wing groups across Europe and then I turned announcements, but instead of a new band vincularles or product of diet, advertisements invited users to complete a survey that asked about their level of education, attitudes toward violence and optimism about their own future.
Arriving via Facebook, Bartlett and his colleagues were able to study more than 10,000 followers of 14 extreme right-wing parties in 11 European countries - all without leaving the office.
"Is a completely new way of doing an investigation," says Bartlett.
Some of the results are not entirely surprising: Online supporters of the right-wing groups tend to be young men and angry about immigration.
However, in a kind of swing, "those who combined his activism in line with offline activism are more reasonable, more democratic and less violent than those who stay behind the computer screen."
The work of demos is just one example of how Facebook is becoming an important new tool in the hands of scientists.
Research centres, medical researchers and scientists politicians are using the site to study everything from health problems for social trends as expressed in the "likes," messages on the walls and status updates.
With more than 800 million active users by adding an average of three pieces of content per day, "supernova of data" of Facebook is creating a boom of research, boosting the number of scholarly papers with the name of the site in the title until almost 800% in the last five years.
For some researchers, the beauty of Facebook is that it enables you to look at the people who you could not acercarte with a file on the street.
"Before, when intentabas surveying people of the British National Party, it was very difficult to identify them."
"You go through the party, and they never would allow you access," says Bartlett.
"Facebook removes all that - you go to them directly."
Others say that the site could provide a way to identify and address the social-health problems.
A recent study by Dr Megan Moreno, of the University of Wisconsin-Madison and his colleagues found that university students who spoke of their feats of binge on Facebook had a significantly higher risk of having problems with drink that students who remained silent on the issue.
Moreno suggests that the fellow students, such as residential advisers, could monitor the site and intervene to help a student who publish too many updates of state with its binge drinking.
"You can't deal with a problem if we can diagnose," said Dimitri Christakis, the co-author of Moreno and director of the Centre for Health, Behavioural Child Development at Seattle Children's Research Institute, told the Washington Post.
"We have found a way to identify children at risk that otherwise would not be diagnosed."
Facebook is also constantly "nudging" to his own people to obtain data.
The Team Supervisor of the site has produced statistics on the state of the relationship and Valentine's Day, the expectation of electoral participation in the middle of the legislative period of 2010, and a National Happiness index (mainly using the information that can be accessed - digital freedom advocates have long argued that the site should make available to other large amount of data for research).
However, Facebook users know that the site is watching you, whether you like it or not - the sacrifice on the power play Scrabble with a friend to thousands of kilometres away is to allow the site undermine your personal information.
But what happens when users of Facebook become part of a survey that do not even know?
While researchers have clear guidelines on how to collect their data out of line, online is a free lunch for all.
"I do not think that many users have thought even in the fact that a researcher could be looking at their profiles," says Neil Selwyn, a sociologist of the Laboratory of Knowledge of London, on a 2006 study conducted with the walls of public Facebook students.
"As far as they were concerned, it was only between them and their friends."
Then there is the question of the methodology.
Even outside line, there is no guarantee that a subject of research this being completely honest.
On Facebook, it is impossible to know that some of the information in a user's profile and the messages of the wall are true.
"What you say on Facebook and what you do outside of Facebook are two completely different things," said Selwyn.
That is why, despite his years as a researcher of technology, Selwyn believes that a pen and a sujetapapeles remain the best research tools that anyone can use.
"There is no substitute for entry into the real world and talk to real people," he says.
"Social research is supposed to be about the social - and a lot of social still happens out of line."
