7 Lessons of the interview loss of Steve Jobs, are in a theater this week
Following the death of Steve Jobs, on 5 October, there were some who compared with Henry Ford - distinguishing the genius of modern technology as the Great inventor.
But what the fan of Apple could find more revealing, in an interview with Jobs recently discovered anew that has been dusted in advance of a series of special projections in the largest markets this week, is how much this meant creative minds about business processes and workflows of products.
It was certainly a designer, dreamer and hippie autorreconocido, but it was also a meticulous and an organizer of the flow flowcharts - a man who believed that many executives were "a disease that is to think that a great idea is 90 percent of the work... [but] there is a huge amount of work between a great idea and a great product."
In 1995, Bob Cringely was developing the television series The Triumph of the nerds (The Triumph of the nerds) on the dawn of the personal computer, and sat for more than an hour with Jobs for an extensive and rare conversation.
At that time had passed barely 10 years since Jobs had been forced to leave Apple, and has worked hard on his new computer company next, waiting for the popular adoption of the Internet.
While a small part of the interview was used in Cringely nerds, said that the original interview disappeared during transport.
It was only after the death of Jobs discovered a full copy VHS in the garage of the director.
This archival material, slightly reprinted, is the basis of Steve Jobs: The Lost interview, 68 minutes, which arrives in cinemas Landmark this Wednesday and Thursday.
For someone known to hate the in-depth interviews, Jobs here seems surprisingly willing to expose their philosophies technological and business strategies.
And very muses.
In four different points throughout the interview, there are great silences between the questions and answers - 10 to 15 seconds of thoughts, where Jobs is clearly weighing their thoughts, seeking clarification.
There are also moments when the perfectionism of Jobs goes to the surface, where it seems impatient due to questions of Cringely, empujándole to go faster towards the issues and arguments of greater importance.
Filmed before the age of Pixar, the iPod or iPhone, there is something strangely prophetic interview in The Lost, when Jobs assesses what sees that other companies are right and wrong, and offers its own vision of the future of computing.
It is one thing to read posthumous assessments of the career of Jobs, but there is something crude oil and inspiring in the Jobs that we see here, the dreamer keen on the verge of greatness.
He has a vision of as you can and must be things.
Not long after explain everything in detail here, and it did.
A quick summary of seven major sequences of The Lost interview:
About how he learned to carry a business:
"Over the years in the business, I always wondered:" Why are you doing things? "And the answers that you are invariably:" Oh, this is just the way it is. "
Nobody knows why he does what he does, in business no one thinks about things very deeply.
That is what I found.
Jobs leads to detail their efforts to simplify the accounts of Apple.
Taken aback by the way they tracked the costs - often starting with a "standard cost" that was as a rule of thumb, and then followed with a "variable" - developed an automated factory that claimed that could determine the costs of trade in detail.
On the joke Pope:
Jobs recounts the "Blue Box" which he built with Steve Wozniak - a device that allows people hackear effectively the telephone company and to make free long-distance calls.
It has written extensively about the device, but the euphoria of Jobs here in describing the Blue Box as an act of empowerment is contagious.
He describes how he and Wozniak proved the box through the use of a public phone, making a call, and then connecting from a network of AT & T to another, while creating a loop with the largest number of satellites as possible.
"We were wrapping things around the world a half-dozen times and gritabas through the public telephone and came back a minute later on the phone to the public next door," says Jobs with a risita.
"We were young and what we learned was that we could build something ourselves that could control billions of dollars in infrastructure around the world."
Us two, we did not know much, but we could build a small thing that could control a giant thing - was a lesson incredible, and I do not believe that Apple had never existed without it.
Jobs continues describing a glorious joke that he and Wozniak nearly abandoned, knocking the Vatican through the Blue Box in the middle of the night and asking to speak with the Pope, as did his best imitation of Henry Kissinger.
As several members of the Catholic hierarchy were called in the middle of the night to talk to the American diplomat, the two broke out in laughter just before the very Pope was excited to go to answer the phone.
Fall in love with the technology (and the sale by telephone with Bill Hewlett):
At the age of 12 years, the hunting of spare parts to build a frequency meter, sought to Bill Hewlett in the telephone directory and I made a call.
Shortly after his telephone conversation of 20 minutes, Jobs got a part-time summer job at Hewlett-Packard.
"That was a considerable influence on me, was the only company that had seen at that age and formed my vision of what was a company and how well they dealt with their employees."
After Jobs became one of the employees of HP who visited the research laboratories of the company in Palo Alto, where he saw "the first table computer ever made."
It was as large as a suitcase, had a small screen cathode tube, and I enamoré him.
Get a trip to HP as a teenager and lose the time with this machine and would write programs for it.
Improvise on innovation:
At various points in the interview, Jobs speaks about inventing new products on the march.
Early in his career, which was devoted to sell a handful of collectors, a customer asked if I could put the whole team.
Working with only 30 days of credit, had to find out the assembly and delivery of finished devices.
Later, while I was at Apple, recalls the battles that clashed in the development of a computer mouse:
"I remember having dramatic arguments... I shouted that it would take five years to create a mouse that would cost $300], and I harté and I went outside and found a designer.
90 days later, we had a mouse that we could build on 15 dollars and that was completely reliable.
On large companies losing strength:
Long before that lead the rebirth of Apple, Jobs prophetically foresaw the way in which many leaders of industry encountered in his vision, and would lose control of their market share.
"I gave that you have worked at IBM or Xerox, for what you do best copiers and printers, and what?"
You have the monopoly of the market share, so the company has no more success.
Sales and marketing departments are increasing success, so are the kind of people who end up running companies and individuals responsible for the products are driven out of the forum for decision-making.
The genius of the products that led to this monopoly position it rots because of people who do not have the notion of good vs. bad products products - the knowledge of the trade.
That is what happened in Xerox...
Xerox could have hijacked the entire computer industry.
Could have been 10 times its size, it could have been the Microsoft in the 1990s...
Took the defeat of the victory.
On innovation as artistic expression:
"There is a huge amount of work between a great idea and a great product... as it develops the big idea, changing and growing."
Learn a lot about the subtleties of the same.
There are sacrifices that you have to do - some things that you can't do that make electrons, glass makes them, the robots, factories make them.
5,000 you have to keep things in your brain - these concepts - align them all at the same time...
In the end it all comes down to taste - exponerte rebate to try to better than a human team has done, and then try to adapt these things that you are doing.
Picasso said that the good artists copy, great artists steal.
We have never had shame about stealing big ideas.
What did in large part to the Macintosh was that the people who were working on it were musicians, poets, artists, zoólogos, historians, which coincidentally were the best computer scientists in the world.
If it were not for the technology, could be doing wonderful things in other areas.
