On the day that the Supreme Court met behind closed doors to discuss the issue politically controversial whether they would accept the challenge to the healthcare law President Obama, two of its justices, Antonin Scalia and Clarence Thomas, were agasajados at a dinner sponsored by the signing of lawyers who will set out the case before the high court.
The occasion was last Thursday, when the nine judges gathered at a preliminary hearing to consider carefully the requests for review.
One of the cases in question was a complaint filed by 26 states defy the total reform of health care passed by Congress last year, a law that has been a rallying cry for conservative activists across the country.
The judges agreed to admit the demand and, in fact, is expected to be a historic plea for five and a half hours in March, and the result will probably will further muddy the presidential race of 2012, which will be in full swing at the time that the court's decision is known.
The lawyer who will appear before the court and will claim that the law should be scrapped will probably be Paul Clement, who served as US attorney general during the administration of George W. Bush.
The signing of lawyers of Clement, Bancroft PLLC, was one of the nearly two dozen companies that helped sponsor the annual dinner of the Federalist Society, a group that has been many years devoted to the defence of the conservative legal principles.
Another signature that sponsored the dinner, Jones Day, represents one of the trade associations that challenged the law, the National Federation of Independent Business.
Another sponsor was the pharmaceutical giant Pfizer Inc., which has a huge financial interest in the outcome of the dispute.
The dinner was held at a hotel in Washington, hours after the court's preliminary hearing on the case.
Attendees was, among others, Mitch McConnell, the most important Republican in the Senate and a declared opponent of the health care law.
The special guests at the dinner? Scalia and Thomas.
Is nothing new: The two judges have been attending events of the Federalist Society for years.
And it is not something that comes into conflict with the ethical standards.
In fact, the judges are exempt from the Code of Conduct governing the actions of the lower federal judges.
If it were, it could be said that fall under the Code of Canon 4c, which says: "A judge can attend events to raise funds to organizations and other related to the law, although the judge may not be a speaker, a guest of honour, or be on the agenda of such an event."
However, the proximity of Scalia and Thomas to two law firms in the case, as well as a company with a huge financial interest, was enough to alarm the activists of ethics in government.
"This impressive breach of ethics and indifference towards the code goes against the demands of several judges that adheres to the court by the same rules that apply to all federal judges," said Bob Edgar, president of Common Common causes (cause).
"The judges were agasajados in a fundraising gala with lawyers who have cases pending before the court."
His appearance and assistance in fundraising for this event undermines any demand for impartiality, and it is unacceptable.
Scalia and Thomas have shown little interest in the critics who say that too easily mix the activity of the court with the agenda driven by groups such as the Federalist Society.
And the wife of Thomas, Ginni is a prominent conservative activist.
On the other hand, the Conservatives argue that is Judge Elena Kagan, who has an ethical problem, not Scalia and Thomas.
Kagan worked as solicitor general for the Obama administration when it introduced the first legal challenges to the law in the court of first instance.
His critics have pushed for Kagan refrain from watching the case, saying it was too involved in defending the law as to now be impartial.
Kagan has not given any indication that it will do.
