ADB urges Asia to help bail out the eurozone
The Asian Development Bank (ADB) has appealed to India and China to prepare to help rescue the eurozone of its sovereign debt crisis to avoid a recession in the long term that would prevent the growth of the Asian economies.
Rajat Nag, managing director of the Asian Development Bank in Manila, said that the two major world's fastest growing economies in the world had to "do everything possible" to speed up the recovery of economic bloc either through the International Monetary Fund or directly through bilateral agreements.
He warned against the BRIC (Brazil, Russia, India, China] countries who are watching the difficulties of Europe in a "impartial" and said that the financial assistance of Asia along with the leadership and European resources would help to avoid a long-term crisis in the global economy.
"We are all in this together."
"So anyone who can help Europe out of the crisis is useful," he told the Financial Times in an interview in the framework of the World Economic Forum in Mumbai.
"Asia may be protected to some extent, but it cannot be immune."
"So if China and India can help, by all means."
The European monetary union has been severely undermined by a sovereign debt crisis in recent months.
In recent days, Italy's borrowing costs have soared dangerously and the prime ministers of Italy and Greece have resigned.
The current sovereign debt crisis in Europe has increased fears that could push the global economy into recession and has led to calls for the major emerging economies to join to help the eurozone to find a solution.
Mr Nag predicted that any support from Asia would be channelled through the IMF, but said that the bilateral assistance - such as buying the bonds of the EU's bailout fund, the European Financial Stability Fund - offered a greater bargaining power for the Asian partners in Europe.
Anand Sharma, India's Minister of Commerce, said that "India is going to do everything possible" to help the eurozone since its own economy was now suffering from the fall in exports and the depletion of foreign capital inflows.
"Nobody wants the eurozone remains unstable and troubled," he said.
"We have monumental challenges and we need to maintain a high level of growth."
"It is not an option, it is an imperative, because where we find jobs for tens of millions of our young men and women."
Others argue that developing economies such as India have no responsibility in helping the rich European when faced with their own and deep economic problems.
Ashutosh Varshney, a professor at Brown University in the US, said that it would be politically very difficult to sell the aid to Europe for the $200 billion people in India, of which up to 800 million live with nearly $2 a day or less.
"At some point you realise that the Greeks retire at the age of 50 years and go on holiday to the beaches and that will not fall well," he said.
Lee Howell, managing director of the World Economic Forum, also questioned why the reserves of India should be used to keep the numerous and well-paid public sector workers Greek, in jobs of companies badly managed, and loss-making as the railways.
Mr Nag said that the eurozone crisis threatens to "significant effects on chain" across Asia.
The Asian Development Bank forecast of 7.5 per cent economic growth in Asia for 2011/12 now faces the "downside risks" due to the threat of Europe.
He said that the vulnerable emerging markets needed to make "contingency plans" to protect themselves from a crisis and significant capital outflows of their economies.
Pentagon serious warnings about the possible cuts in defence
Secretary of Defense Leon Panetta, calentó Congress on Monday, warning that the automatic cuts looming budget could undermine national security and trigger a chain reaction in financial from the corridors of the Pentagon, on the battlefields of Afghanistan, the assembly chains civilians.
The Pentagon is already digesting the $450 billion in cuts over the next decade, but now fears a further reduction of 600 billion or more in cuts that may be imminent if Congress fails to reach an agreement on spending.
"The impact of these cuts would be devastating for the department," Panetta said in a letter to senators John McCain, Republican of Arizona, and Lindsey Graham, Republican of South Carolina.
He said that the failure of Congress to reach an agreement on the budget and its consequence, the so-called "kidnapping", would lead to a 23 per cent of global reductions and a high of many new projects.
"A cut so great, this applied indiscriminately, would make the most of our naval construction projects and could not be carried out - you cannot buy three-quarters of a boat or a building - and seriously harming other modernization efforts," Panetta wrote to the senators.
"Also we would be forced to remove many of our civil servants involuntarily, and due to the reduction would be so quickly, it is almost certain that we would have to license civilians in order to meet the target."
"These changes would break faith with those who keep our army and seriously would damage the readiness."
The cuts in time would reach to the combat troops, said Panetta.
"While funding for times of war in the accounts of overseas contingency operations are not directly affected by the kidnapping, the efforts of the war would be adversely affected by the severe disruption in the budgets of basis," Panetta warned.
"The recruitment of staff would be reduced, leading to delays in contracts and supervision of the contract that supports the war."
"The staff on the payroll would be reduced, leading to delays in payments to suppliers in time of war, and the legal and political support would be interrupted."
The two senators had written to Panetta 10 days ago, asking for information about the possible impact of the automatic cuts in the Department of Defense.
"The consequence of a kidnapping in the Department of Defense would lead to a rapid decline in the United States as the main military power in the world."
"We are firmly against such draconian action," the senators said in a joint statement Monday evening, when published the letter to Panetta.
"This is not an outcome that can live, and it is certainly not one that we should impose ourselves."
"The kidnapping is a threat to the national security interests of the United States, and must not be allowed to happen."
If the letter to Panetta and the recent warnings of the senators will increase the pressure for a budget compromise or intensified calls to exempt the Pentagon cuts remains to be seen.
Panetta has been increasingly vocal about the possible cuts, despite the fact that came to a job at the top of the Pentagon with years of experience in budgets in Congress and the White House and knowing that it faced difficult decisions.
At a press conference last week, Defense Secretary painted a grim picture of what could be ahead - an army with a shell, but not a core.
"It is a ship without sailors."
"It is a brigade without bullets."
"It is an air wing without sufficient trained pilots."
"It is a paper tiger, an army barracks, buildings and bombs without enough trained soldiers to carry out the mission," Panetta said in his opening remarks at the Pentagon.
"It is a force that is suffering from low morale, poor preparation and is not able to keep up to date with the potential adversaries."
"In fact, invites aggression..."
In an appendix to his letters to McCain and Graham, Panetta provides new details of how the cuts "generate significant operational risks: Delay in time of crisis response, conflicts and disasters; severely limits our ability to be deployed and previously committed around the world; and poses an unacceptable risk in future combat operations."
And Panetta said that some of the major defence projects could face the axe, including those who are already being tested and some only in the early stages of planning.
The list includes F35 fighter plane, the Joint Strike Fighter, a new bomber planned, the next-generation ballistic submarine, the new combat ship coastline and the new combat vehicle on land that the Army and the Navy need to replace the HumVee.
Halt development and the additional evidence of F35 could generate about $80 billion in savings over 10 years, but his supporters say that is the next vital step to improve and address potential threats from China and other rivals.
As a lie
A look at the most recent headlines shows us how serious and pervasive are deception and lies in everyday life.
The Republican presidential candidate Herman presidential is busy exchanging accusations of sexual harassment with several women; each side accused of lying to the other.
The trustees of the State University of Pennsylvania have been charged with perjury for allegedly concealing reports which said that a football coach was withdrawn sexually abusing children.
Last week, the French president, Nicolas Sarkozy, was "caught" with an open microphone saying the US president, Barack Obama, Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu is a liar.
Lying has destroyed careers and troubled countries.
Congressman for New York and exhibicionista on the Internet, Anthony Weiner, made the ridiculous with their denials rebatidos quickly by the irrefutable proof.
The former presidential candidate John Edwards has been accused of offences in the financing of the campaign related to the cover-up of an extra-marital relationship.
And, again, no one who lived will ever forget the media circus unleashed by President Bill Clinton during his second term by lying about his sexual relationship with Monica Lewinsky.
Are widespread legends about the traps in the examinations of school and university.
There have been cases in which teachers have given the answers from the tests to students in order to be better seen in their assessments of performance.
Mentors should be taught to the contrary are sending the message that lying and cheating are acceptable.
How deception we are?
On any given day, studies show that you can lie anywhere from 10 to 200 times.
That is for sure, many of these lies are white lies.
Another study showed that the unknown cheating three times in the first 10 minutes of unknown.
Detect lies, or "the location of lies," is an essential skill to acquire all, for reasons both personal and professional.
Far from being a game of table similar to, for example, charade, where the goal is to say: "You have," the detection of deception is a branch of the serious knowledge based on scientific data obtained during the last six decades in prestigious universities who conducted in-depth research projects, especially in psychology and physiology.
One of the results of the research is that the old myths about the lies have been rebatidos.
The liars do look in the eyes.
Does not always tartamudean, stuttering out, ruborizan or worry.
We cannot conclude either that the liars are difficult to detect or expose.
A lie detector can be trained to learn the truth about the structure of the declaration, the expressions microfaciales, training of questions and the times.
I spent several years exploring scientific discoveries about the deception in the vast and always emerging body of knowledge, and it was clear that the detection of deception is a modern technique that is easy to learn and help navigate our complex world - especially if their professional responsibilities include the recruitment, interviews, or the management of negotiations.
The good liars have the ability to read well to others, making them feel at ease, running their own emotions and felt intuitively how others perceive.
We know from research that the extrovertidos lie more than the introvertidos, that men are more telling "lies geared towards themselves," while women say more lies "geared towards others" -- usually to protect the feelings of someone -- that married people lie less frequently to their partners that people who are not married (but the lies that usually say tend to be "huge").
We also know that if you are perceived as a malefactor, others will feel less guilty to lying.
How to know if someone is lying?
First, observe the normal conduct of the subject.
This is called "to create a baseline."
Aid to provide benchmarks to measure after the changes.
Look at the position of the subject, laughing and vocal feature.
It is better to know if someone normally golpetea with the foot all the time for not making accusations unfair when I see the golpeteando feet in the middle of the meeting.
Then, seek groups of misleading behavior, verbal and non-verbal.
Consider these groups of behaviour as warning signs, not as proof of deception.
People who cheat can freeze the upper part of the body to try to remember their history, they can point their feet toward the door, leaning toward an exit, changing its position significantly or exhibit a "confession postentrevista" -- that exaggerated sigh of relief and change of position once all the hard questions have ended.
Interrogators are often falsely that the interview is over, only to find that postentrevista relief.
It also draws attention to the vocabulary of the subject.
Scott Peterson got the leg to the bottom and used the last time while stated that his wife killed was alive, launching a search for her at the national level.
People who cheat can also use a language distanciador: "I did not have sexual relations with that woman, Miss Lewinsky..." or repeat a difficult question in full.
The most common verbal indicators are subtle.
Anyone can use a lot of "restrictive language" when a difficult question to answer: "Well... to tell the truth... so what I was... in my view."
That makes the response is a perception rather than a fact and is often a warning sign.
There is no magic formula to detect lies, but to develop skills to uncover deception is possible.
These skills will improve the chances of anyone to avoid being victimized by the scam artists in their professional and personal lives.
The controversial plan of the pipeline diverted after the threat of US delay in its approval
Days after the Obama administration threatened to delay the adoption of a planned oil pipeline from Canada to the Gulf of Mexico -- infuriating the unions, while apaciguaba environmentalists -- the company that seeks to build the pipeline says he is ready to redirect the project to return to return it.
TransCanada said on Monday night that move the pipeline planned outside the area of ecologically sensitive Sandhills in Nebraska, and is confident that the project will win approval.
The company announced the decision at a press conference in the Capitol in Nebraska.
The manager of TransCanada, Alex Pourbax, said that the company maintains its confidence that over time the pipeline will be approved, albeit with a different route.
This comes after the announcement last week by the State Department to delay the decision by a federal permit for the project to explore potential new routes to avoid areas of Nebraska Sandhills and the Ogallala aquifer, a vast underground water supplies.
"This is a real path of progress," said Representative Lee Terry, a Republican from Nebraska, to Fox News.
The new environmental review ordered by the Department of State is possible that apart from any decision until 2013, after next year's elections, although officials denied that politics was involved in the decision.
Obama, in a written statement last week, described the decision as the State Department's request, and they expressed its full support.
The pipeline, 1,700 kilometres would stretch from Canada to the Gulf of Mexico.
Lead 700,000 barrels per day of the province of Alberta to refineries in Texas.
For this, it would be necessary to crossed six states.
Is hated by environmentalists, but beloved by the working groups, who have opted for the estimated 20,000 jobs linked to the pipeline.
But Nebraska lawmakers opposed to the plan are weighing legislation to force a move away from the region of Sandhills and the Ogallala aquifer, the largest source of drinking water and irrigation.
The current environmental impact study of the State Department found that the project had only limited adverse environmental impacts, but the source of the energy industry said that the department's inspector general has ordered an independent test of the review process, focusing on two issues.
One is whether the Member of the lobby hired by TransCanada, Paul Elliott, who was an adviser to Hillary Clinton's campaign in 2008, represents a conflict of interest for the programme.
The other is whether a firm that was contracted to conduct the original study was an inappropriate choice because he was linked to TransCanada.
