Climate adversity halt the economy
During the first year of management of Mario Lopez Valdez, in Sinaloa has increased unemployment and informality, fell foreign investment and the economy shrank
The 2011 is a year that will be remembered in economic history of Sinaloa, this is the first year of government of Mario Lopez Valdez, self-styled of change, which generated great expectations to developments in the economy, but given the climatic adversity of start of the year, there is growth, instead it is a deterioration in the main indicators of economic development.
The low temperatures in February, in addition to causing billions in losses for the agricultural sector, limited the scope of the state economy to grow, caused a contraction of economic activity in general of 3.6 per cent in the first half of the year, justified mainly by the historic collapse of 31.16% in agriculture, which affected the dynamism of the other economic sectors.
According to the report of the impact of frost, issued by the Mexican Council for Sustainable Rural Development, had damage to 582 thousand 835 hectares cultivated, of which the 78.03 percent suffered total damage and the remaining 21.07 per cent had partial damage, the victims were the main crops of vegetables, corn and chick peas, lupin.
The fall in economic activity has generated, until November, a steady increase in unemployment in the state, according to the National Institute of Statistics and Geography the state unemployment rate during the first three quarters of the year saw a rapid growth, because while from January to March 1,053 sinaloenses 55 were unemployed, with a rate of 4.53 percent of the economically active population, for the second quarter the rate became 5.28 percent, and the average between July and September continued rising to 6.19 percent, a rate that number of people cast more than 74 thousand sinaloenses unemployed, an increase over the first half of 18 thousand 969 individuals.
Lesser liquidity
Unemployment in Sinaloa during the year is multifaceted, to the economist Gerardo Lopez Cervantes, director of the School of Economic and Social Sciences of the UAS, the growth of unemployment can be explained indirectly, depending on the actions of public policy have been made.
"What we are seeing is a growth in unemployment that has to do with a number of factors, including the loss of liquidity in the market for effects of a restriction of resources for the legislation that was passed in Congress to combat money laundering, as for the people who he seizes dollars illegally is not easy for the work, and used to invest in something", he said.
Detained migration
Lopez Cervantes pointed out that the rise in unemployment, there is also a demographic factor.
"The number of people who are going to the state in search of work abroad, in the United States has been restricted, first by the difficulties to enter, and secondly because entering already have too many difficulties in finding work, these people is falling and is demanding jobs here in the state, which means that unemployment rises," he said.
Informal sector
The analysis of the labour market sinaloense is compounded when considering the high level of informality that prevails among working conditions, according to the INEGI, 60.38 percent of the working population in the state is working without being contribute as worker with no institution of social security.
Joined to unemployment and informality, another of the state's labor problems are low wages, the body has the lowest wages in the country, according to the records of the Mexican Social Security Institute and the Ministry of Labour and Social Security.
The average monthly income of workers sinaloenses was, until September, 5,352 billion pesos, well below the national average, located in 7,375 pesos.
Of FDI contraction
Coupled with the fall in economic activity and the rise in unemployment during 2011 recorded the largest decrease of Foreign Direct Investment in the last 10 years, according to the Ministry of Economic Affairs from January to June FDI 69.7 state joined 630 billion dollars, representing a fall of 87.74% compared to the $143 $312 5 million registered during the same period of the previous year.
For its part, the Ministry of Economic Development of the state government recorded a total investment of 17 thousand 280 billion pesos in the year, mainly from companies in the tertiary sector.
The debt 
Before the stage of economic contraction, the government of the state requested in July to state congress approval of a loan for 3 billion pesos, which would be earmarked for investment in infrastructure projects in 18 municipalities, with the aim of reviving the economy, the approval of the local congress was for an amount of €2,600 million pesos, and until November have not seen the benefits of debt in any sector of the state economy.
Reactions to
For representatives of the business sector, the first year of government of Mario Lopez Valdes gives shows a lack of management capacity of the government.
Miguel Loredo López, president of the National Chamber of Industry of the transformation, expressed that during 2011 it lacked the harmonisation of wills of the various sectors, including the state's own government.
"The performance of the economy in Sinaloa during this year has been very poor, we must work hard to regain the ground lost in this year, in 2012, we must redouble efforts, lacked need to align the effort of all, and above all the good progress synchronized because of this new team of government, we hope that next year will be much better," he said.
Economic slow pace
Loredo Lopez said that events such as the frost in the beginning of the year they stopped the state economy and restricted their performance and growth.
"The low economic flow is the product of several events, including the frost, one of the main effects has been a slow economy that does not return quickly enough to generate an economic dynamism that will have an acceptable level of flow in the processes, products and services, and therefore we are closing at the end of the year, well below the expectations that we had," he said.
Redefine vocation
For Teodoro Salazar Uriarte, president of the Confederation of Mexican employers in Sinaloa, said that requires the state to productive activities of greater dynamism.
"In general terms we have noted that it has been working, we believe that it is necessary to develop a long-term program to redefine the vocation and the state's economic course, because it is important to detonating the full potential of the material and human resource of Sinaloa," he said.
By work to
The chairman of the Coparmex stressed the importance of establishing a vision of the future that channel the efforts of the government.
"In general terms, I would say that the government has been striving to give good results in various areas, in terms of economic development, there is some progress but it is important to develop a long-term programme," he said.
Noted that the current administration has shown progress in its way to drive public policy.
"There are elements that may say that the government is being more inclusive, what I can say is that there is work done and I believe that the government is aware that there is work to be done," he said.
