Court validates "analogue switch-off" in Mexico in 2015
The switch from analogue to digital signals is one of the most important changes that the world has seen in recent years
The Supreme Court of Justice of the Nation (SCJN) dismissed constitutional disputes that brought the Senate and the Chamber of Deputies against the presidential decree that advances the so-called "analogue switch-off" from 2021 to 2015, failing to meet the eight votes needed to overturn it.
A minority of four ministers, including the president of the Court, Juan Silva Meza, found that the President Felipe Calderón is not exceeded its authority by issuing the decree detailing the actions to make the transition to digital terrestrial television.
With this outcome, the constitutional controversy promoted by the Senate of the Republic, was dismissed for failing to reach a qualified majority of eight votes for the Court to rule on the constitutionality of the decree or Unconstitutionality, and this is in force.
The draft judgment drawn up by the Minister Olga Sánchez Cordero, proposed to declare unconstitutional the decree, owing to the regulation of the subjects of radio and television is a right reserved by law to the Federal Telecommunications Commission (Cofetel), in contravention of the principles of hierarchical subordination and reserve of law.
Voted in favour of the draft only Zaldívar, Jorge Mario Pardo, Margarita Moon and own Sánchez Cordero.
With this argument, both the Senate and the Chamber of Deputies promoted two constitutional disputes to contest the decree, and to accept the demands, the minister Sánchez Cordero suspended the implementation of the decree and all actions as he prepared for the digital transition.
Full of ministers decided to dismiss the case brought by the Chamber of Deputies, without going to the discussion of the draft, also in charge of the minister Sánchez Cordero.
In his speech, the president said does not agree with the arguments of the project, in the sense that the federal executive cannot structure through general rules measures so that the public administration prepare.
"Nor do I believe that if it did it would affect the autonomy of the regulatory body," and recalled that the planning of public policies in strategic areas such as the telecommunications sector within the federal executive, who is constitutional mandate, the stewardship of the state.
The switch from analogue to digital signals is one of the most important changes that the world has seen in recent years, and translates into a better use of the radio spectrum, a better quality of the signal and more channels.
Postpone the change, he argued, would be to postpone the benefits of digitisation, which implies a decision of public interest, which is not only a technical dimension, "because it covers economic, social, political and national security."
These issues, he stressed, "require the operation of the whole system established under the principle of economic stewardship of the state, includes a group of powers that the Constitution leads to the power of the state Executive."
Recalled that a large number of countries around the world has already completed the digital transition, and has done so through the Executive, despite having highly specialized technical bodies.
We cannot conclude that the Executive, challenged by issuing the decree, which will in any way the purview of Congress, since it is providing administrative enforcement of laws issued by the Legislature, he assured.
Look at the possibility of a count "vote by vote" in Michoacán
According to data produced by the Prep the difference between first and second place in the election for governor is only 27 per cent, even without the votes counted for 879 6,000 74 minutes total.
The possibility of counting "vote by vote" is a reality in terms of the electoral process this year in Michoacan, where according to data produced by the Preliminary Electoral Results Program (Prep) the difference between first and second place in the election for governor is only 27 per cent, even without the votes counted for 879 6,000 74 minutes total.
In this regard, the chairman of the General Council of the Electoral Institute of Michoacán, Maria de los Angeles Llanderal Zaragoza, recalled that a few days ago, barely on 9 November, the electoral body adopted a series of guidelines in order to harmonize the local rules with the federal reform in electoral matters.
As you will remember, Miachoacán not accredited its Constitution nor his Electoral Code of the state or its Electoral Justice Act, which Congress approved reforms of the state shortly before the legal deadline for concluding that could come into force in the current electoral process and the governor, Leonel Godoy Rangel omitted its publication on schedule in the Official Periodic Law of the State, on the grounds that he had some reservations.
The same 9 November, the Supreme Court of Justice of the Nation (SCJN) settled the dispute constitucional promoted by the local legislature and described as "illegal and invalid" the vote of the state agent to constitutional reforms, which does not have the right to "punish or veto."
Interviewed on the possibility of the "vote by vote," Maria de los Angeles Llanderal explained that thanks to the approval of the remarks made by the General Council of the IEM it will be possible to implement total and partial counts of the vote by the local electoral body.
That way, the partial recount of votes, in one or more electoral packages, may be on the assumptions that: The results of the records do not coincide; there is no record of voting and counting in the file of the box or not in possession of the chairman of the same; or, if there are obvious errors or disruptions of the proceedings.
In addition, the total count of the vote received in all the boxes of the election will take place when there is evidence that the difference between the candidate presumed winner of the election in question and which has won the second place in the vote, is equal to or less than one percentage point; if and when at the start of the sitting there is the express request of the representative of the party and/or coalition that applied to the second of the candidates.
The total count of the vote will take place at the end of the counting if Extrabudgetary establishes that the difference between the candidate and the presumed winner located in second place is equal to or less than one percentage point, if and when there is a specific request from the representative of the political party whose candidate was in second place, in which case will be electoral packages that have been the subject of partial recount.
It is worth mentioning that in this situation is the choice of Morelia, where according to the Prep the difference between the first and second place is only with 0.16 percent, although without counting the votes of 129 of the 923 total minutes.
