Will be formed on Wednesday the new Italian government
The designated prime minister, Mario Monti, will meet tomorrow with the chairman of Italy to present the new government will face a crisis that has put the country on the brink of economic disaster
The Italian prime minister-designate, Mario Monti, will meet on Wednesday with the president of Italy to present the new government will face a crisis that has put Italy on the brink of economic disaster and has endangered the entire eurozone.
A statement from the presidential palace announced that Monti, appointed on Sunday, will meet on Wednesday with the president, Giorgio Napolitano, to confirm that can form a government.
It is expected to present a cabinet made up mostly of technocrats, although it is not clear when the new executive will assume the post.
Monti said that the president will submit the outcome of its talks with political parties in his attempt to form a government.
"I would like to confirm my complete confidence in the ability of our country to overcome this difficult stage," said the former European Commissioner for journalists.
Monti did not say explicitly that will be able to form a government but the tone of his comments indicated that the obstacles have been overcome.
"The framework is now staccato," he added.
Monti has completed the process of forming a government in less than three days, much less than normal, while Italy fight a political and financial crisis that has pushed the cost of its debt to unsustainable levels.
The new administration led by former European Commissioner Monti should adopt a harsh austerity package demanded by European leaders to restore battered confidence in Italy.
Underlining the pressure on Monti to hurry up, the volatility of the markets posted the bond yields on 10-year Italian BTP above 7 per cent, the level at which Greece and Ireland were forced to be rescued.
Emma Marcegaglia, head of Confindustria, the Italian employers, told the press after meeting with Monti: "We said that we would support a lot to this government."
We believe that this government is the last opportunity for Italy out of this emergency situation.
The chances of success of Monti were driven considerably by the support of the party LDP of Silvio Berlusconi, whom the crisis forced to resign on Saturday.
"We believe that the efforts of Professor Monti are destined to have a good result," he said to the press Angelino Alfano, secretary of the center-right party.
The support of the LDP, the biggest party in Italy, is significant because until now many of its members had been opposed to the government of majority technocrat who is forming Monti.
Parliamentary support
The new government of Monti must have a strong parliamentary support to implement what is likely to be unpopular austerity reforms.
Any blockage or delay in their efforts could lead to a new and devastating attack on the financial markets.
The Italian association of foreign banks joined the pressure to warn that a failure of Monti would be a disaster.
Monti began on Monday its consultations with political parties, trade unions and business groups, as well as with youth organizations and women.
Will put an end to his round of meetings on Tuesday night.
Monti was appointed on Sunday by Napolitano, who has enabled a transition extremely fast in response to the crisis.
After a brief respite at the end of the week, when it became clear that Berlusconi would resign, the costs of Italian debt have now returned to critical levels between the uncertainty about whether the new prime minister will be successful.
Rescue Italy, with a public debt of 1.8 billion, would be too much for the current financial defenses of the eurozone.
Monti said that his government should last until the next elections, scheduled for 2013, despite widespread predictions about which politicians only give him time to implement the reforms before early elections.
Monti said that he would like to include politicians in his cabinet, but the big parties insist that must be formed only by technicians, an indication of their objections to a process required by the financial pressure.
Political sources noted that the mutual distrust and disagreements between the parties are complicating the attempt to include political figures.
