Go to Costa Rica is a dream come true for us, too.
This is only the second time in South and Central America and until now has been great.
I was in Costa Rica only once and holidays; it is a country so beautiful and I believe that we will be able to stay a few days there.
So excited that we carry our music there.
I ask because there is a kind of devotion to the band, the fan living with intensity the previous days.
What do you say to their most ardent supporters?
Thank you for staying on our side through all these years.
We took almost 21 years to reach Costa Rica; thank you for having waited so long and we regret that it has taken so long to get there.
Some people even refers to his concert as the largest show of the year.
Does that adds a bit of pressure on his visit?
Some of the larger shows that we have fallen over the past 21 years occurred during the last couple of weeks.
We touch a couple of giant shows in Sao Paulo and we hope that we have put into shape for this concert in Costa Rica.
In truth, we are very eager to play there.
We love this country, we love surfear and the jungle; for both, Costa Rica is among the best in the world.
How was that discovered Costa Rica and its waves to surfear?
We have a lot of friends who are surfeadores and I have a great friend who lives in Tamarindo and waves there are incredible.
My friends are always going to surfear to Costa Rica and Nicaragua, along with Mexico, are great places to surfear; this was how we learn, by people who loves the surfing.
To see the tour, have been handing out huge shows with many songs.
What they have planned for his presentation in Costa Rica?
As we have never touched there before, then we do not have any restrictions on what we can do.
We will try to give the best show possible with a good variety of songs; we will try to touch on a couple of songs each album and give our fan a good and diverse repertoire.
You never repeat the repertoire.
Why is this?
I think it is partly because we have nine discs and can touch more than 120 songs and each likes different songs, so it is difficult to choose which songs touch every night.
When we have two or three songs in the repertoire that we are now not to touch, that keeps us focused and also keeps us surprised because it reminds us of why we liked these songs and that we may have forgotten.
That makes the show more interesting for us and, therefore, I think it becomes more interesting for people.
With this tour, are celebrating 20 years of record.
Looking back, it is hard to believe everything we have achieved?
Yes, absolutely.
First, I believe that none of us can imagine that we would be in a large rock band and have done so for more than 20 years ago that seems like a dream.
We continue to count our blessings and we are very excited that we can continue to make music together.
We all want and we love to create music.
We are fortunate to go to places in the world to those who always wanted to go.
Things could not be better for us.
What it meant for you have been a fundamental part of the emergence of grunge?
It has always been an honour to be part of this group of big bands.
We are very friends of the people of Soundgarden, Mudhoney and Alice in Chains.
It is surprising when a movement stems from a group of friends and is something rare.
From time to time, there is a band of a city, but it is much more strange when five or ten bands come at the same time in the same city.
We are proud and honoured to be part of the group of Seattle.
Still we touch with some of them from time to time.
Last year, we were in a festival with Alice in Chains and were in Canada with Mudhoney, Soundgarden we saw in his tour, so we are fortunate to be friends of all of them still and we are honoured to be part of that sound of Seattle that emerged.
It is also very strange that a band like you stand united and with the same members for so long.
Yes, four of us are together for 21 years and Matt (Cameron) we joined 13 years ago, which, by itself, is much more time than last many gangs.
First, I believe that we are fortunate to be still alive and, secondly, we are all concerned about others.
We are all very close friends and, thanks to this, have also been opened musical avenues that give freedom to each of experience.
We trust each other with the music of each and could not be better.
The relationship of you with the word fame has not been simple; however, thanks to its success, have been able to do what they want.
How find a balance sheet?
As we have been growing, it has been easier to find a balance sheet.
We do not be too of tour because it is easy to fall into that game of the large crowds and the people who loves your music.
While one remembers that people are there for the music, that you remember that you must respect the music and what brought, without just concentrate on being famous and be a rock star, something that none of us really interested in.
How recalls his another project Mother Love bone?
I believe that we wrote songs and very good at the principle was something grand.
We were a band for nearly three years and never published a disk until after he died Andy (Andrew).
There were many frustrations because both duration and the most important thing is that we are still very friends of Bruce (Fairweather) and Greg (Gilmore), which began in the band with us and when I hear a song or see a photo I think of the incredible person that Andy was and how I was laughing, was always a pleasure to go to work, laugh, talk about music and football and much more.
It was an amazing human being and we were shocked.
The national band The Robertas will open the show in Costa Rica.
Is it true that you are familiar with his work, especially Eddie Vedder, and that is why the chose to openness?
Yes, the production we sent videos with several proposals and that was the band that we liked, so we are eager to see what The Robertas can offer in alive and must be very entertaining.
Why are always changing the letter of Yellow Ledbetter live?
That is a question for Ed (Eddie Vedder), so I do not know.
He sings and I think that it does with the first thing that would happen.
How downward, what are your influences?
Are so many.
Within the first that spring to mind are Geezer Butler, John Entwistle, C. J. Ramone, John Doe, Paul McCartney, Chuck Dukowski...
There are so many who could talk all afternoon on the bear that I love.
How has managed to Pearl Jam maintain relevant the grunge despite not being a fashion?
I think that all of us we always feel a bit disconnected from the word grunge.
When I think about it, it reminds me of the bands that I mentioned earlier, as Mudhoney, Soundgarden, nirvana and all that emerged at the same time, and, if there is relevant now, I think that is a wonderful thing because it is music that is worth listening and Mudhoney bands and music are doing better now than ever.
At the beginning, his music had a darker content and now has become more positive.
Why is this change?
It is interesting because I think there are a couple of songs on the new album that might seem lighter, but there are also songs, such as The End or Just Breathe songs that qualify as very dark, although it may sound a little positive.
With both, when Ed touched me, I wept when I heard the songs and are deeply dark.
I believe that when far and there are some trauma in your life and you lose to a family member or a friend, these things are beginning to influence your art and your music and those two songs, surely, is that for me.
Also, I think it can be a happy person and still be able to make music that is dark.
