It was the work of caleño that identified the body of Alfonso Cano
A lofoscopista of Cali went down in history as the man who confirmed the death of "Alfonso Cano."
The work of these officials is key.
On 4 November, a lofoscopista CTI Cali went down in history as the man who confirmed the identity of the maximum leader of the FARC, "Alfonso Cano," through the comparison of their fingerprints.
Of the seven lofoscopistas working in the CTI seccional, this week visiting "availability" Eliazar Gonzáles, a man of Puerto Tejada leading 21 years working in the area of judicial inquiry.
At the start of his career, Gonzáles worked in municipalities of collided, where many times had to enter the country for more than five days in the jungle to arrive at the site where the bodies were to be identified.
In 2000 was moved to the capital of Valle and then to make the appropriate courses, has specialized in lofoscopia, which is the study of the skin of friction, that is to say, the palms and feet.
The week of operation against alias Alfonso Cano to Eliazar warned him that carry minimum clothes for three days.
Something big is expected.
Friday in the night went to the Cauca in a helicopter from Palmyra.
I knew that was supposed to identify two corpses and suspected that one of them was the man who ran the world's oldest guerrilla, so I asked him to carry the fingerprint card of Guillermo León Sáenz (his real name).
However, when it came to the research team to the site where the body was not recognized by their physical appearance, because it was very different from what he had seen in the media.
Was without a beard, dressed as a farmer in the area, without glasses and much thinner.
Fingerprints but do not lie.
Accompanied by a magnifying glass galtoniana, ink, a transplantador and a flashlight, Eliazar compared the fingerprints of the corpse with those of the card.
His eye is not ruled: Was "Alfonso Cano."
That same night, the man who hails from Puerto Tejada was commissioned to confirm the defense minister, Juan Carlos Pinzón, that it was the maximum leader of the FARC.
In search of the
For a dactiloscopista Sijín of Cali's recognition that made the president Juan Manuel Santos to Eliazar González, at the press conference for the operation against "grey", is very significant.
Many people do not know our work.
The dactiloscopia is an exact science, no margin of error, which can be key in solving crimes.
Apart from the identification of bodies, the lofoscopistas support investigations for crimes such as theft and manslaughter and confirm the identity of those captured.
When caught, many criminals are false or bonds have no papers.
We will take fingerprinting and seek in the database.
Told the investigator that, in a case of theft, I had to remove a piece of the wall of a house, because in that place the thief had supported its power to draw a strong box full of jewels and money.
"The walls are difficult because they are not appropriate to draw a land fingerprints, but in this case we were able to obtain the footprint of the entire hand and identify the offender, who had participated in various thefts," recalled.
Fingerprints may also exclude or reaffirm suspects in murder cases.
Recently found a man dead, with bottles of spirits around them.
Through research, it was determined that a family member could be suspected of the crime and, indeed, a mark on the bottle was.
Although this does not guarantee that was the killer, they located at the scene of the crime.
A CTI dactiloscopista explained that the objects' fingerprints are drawn with physical or chemical reagents. "
When they appear, it uses a transplantador or tape to lift them.
After this, the impressions are sent to Asif, which is the database delinquency, or to the Registry.
"The problem is that there are still many undocumented Colombians," said the CTI expert.
He clarified that not everything is as shown in the television programme CSI.
As well as not everything that shines is gold, not everything it touches becomes mark.
However, if it can be used, if it makes the comparison.
The "outraged" defy authorities in New York
Hundreds of demonstrators in the Square agolpaban Zuccotti to camp out.
A large part the eviction order and moved to a nearby paruqe.
The members of the movement took Wall Street defied this Tuesday, authorities in New York to try to enter again, under the umbrella of a court order, to the square in Manhattan where they were evicted from early morning and try to occupy another park of the Big Apple.
Hundreds of demonstrators agolpaban at Zuccotti Square, where they wanted access through a court order allowing the "indignant" return to camp out in the place, while another part of the movement responded to the eviction occupy a park further north of the city, where there has been new arrests.
"Our idea is that, if the court does not allow us to return to camp out in the square, we are going to install somewhere else and we will continue the legal battle to return to Zuccotti, as well as through peaceful sit-ins and demonstrations," said one of the spokesmen of the movement "took Wall Street," Mark Bray.
Bray elaborated that the response of the "outraged" at the eviction of his camp personally dictated by the Mayor of New York, Michael Bloomberg, came to court, where Judge Lucy Billings issued an order banning the forced evacuation of the place and allowed the demonstrators to remain camped out.
In addition, the "indignant" proceeded to the occupation of a new park located at the confluence of the central Canal Street and Sixth Avenue, near the entrance to the Holland Tunnel, which connects New York and New Jersey, and ownership of the parish of Trinity Church.
At least for an hour managed to take the place, but then the police came and proceeded to detain some of the demonstrators, although he could not confirm the specific figure, while Efe assured that saw several journalists who were also handcuffed.
The organization ensures that there are several hundred people who had been installed at that point, which has already been sent a delegation of religious leaders in a show of support for the members of the movement and has tried to mediate with the Police.
Meanwhile, Zuccotti Square - which is a forum of private property remains closed pending the conclusion of a court hearing scheduled for this same Tuesday in which they must examine the legality of the evacuation of this morning.
Posted some of the demonstrators were carrying so far at this time and distributed copies of the court order and even delivered to the players who were guarding the square, causing "some small clashes," said Bray, who complained that some officers beat the demonstrators.
The court order prohibits the authorities to evict members of took Wall Street or implement "laws that were published after the occupation began or ban protesters to re-enter the park with tents or other properties that used previously."
The Mayor Bloomberg indicated to the press that, due to the court order, the city had suspended the reopening of space to the public and to the demonstrators, who warned, however, that local laws do not allow them to re-install with tents and sleeping bags.
District personally defended the eviction carried out dawn of Zuccotti Square, an operation in which they proceeded to around 200 arrests and that it was decided because the protesters were "violating the law."
Bloomberg explained that gave the order to evacuate the place because it was turning "in a place where people were not to protest, but to violate the laws and, in some cases, to do harm to others," because "some businesses had received threats" and neighbors feared "for their quality of life."
"The eviction of this morning was disgusting and shows that Bloomberg is more interested in preserving the financial interests than those of American workers," added the spokesman of the movement, who accused the mayor of 'lack of respect for freedom of expression. "
Those responsible for "took Wall Street" also indicated that they intend to organise "great actions" for Thursday in collaboration with community organizations and trade unions, to commemorate the two months for the protests, which began on 17 September.
