Japan is reborn after the earthquake
GDP grows 1.5 percent thanks to the domestic consumption and puts an end to the spiral of declines that began in March
Since last March, the Japanese economy was paralyzed, still convalescing by the devastating earthquake that became a nuclear crisis, the worst disaster the country which suffered from Japan's since World War II.
The first estimates of the government Tokyo material losses estimated at $300 billion, a blow that, despite the difficult global context, seems to have eased.
After three consecutive quarters of declines, the figure of Gross Domestic Product between July and September served to turn the page, definitely: GDP rose 1.5 percent compared with the previous quarter and a 6% annualized rate.
The recorded in the second quarter - for the Japanese, the fiscal year begins in March 2012 - is, moreover, the highest rate of growth since the period from January to March 2010.
The recovery is explained, in part, for the rally of the purchase of machinery to restore the areas ravaged by the earthquake and subsequent tsunami.
Indeed, companies increased their investment in a 1.1%, compared to 0.9% decline in capital expenditure to be observed from January to March, the first decline after six months of uninterrupted increases.
However, the real trigger of the Japanese economy is not based solely on the Keynesian stimulus that invites to take advantage of the crisis to reinforce - or rebuild - infrastructure, use the shortcomings to grow from scratch.
Japan has aroused, above all, thanks to the development of domestic consumption, which currently accounts for 60% of Japan's GDP.
This variable climbed 1%, driven by the increase in spending on cars, travel and leisure activities.
The stigma yen
Tokyo has been entrusted to the internal market, when the yen, Japan's currency -- has become one of the "values haven" selected by investors fleeing the debt crisis in the euro zone and the murky forecasts for US, a privilege that hangs like a bombshell in the accounts of exporting companies.
With a stronger currency, the products are more expensive abroad, a serious setback for a country whose economic survival is determined by the health of large groups of technology.
Toyota or Sony, for example, blaming their weak results between July and September to the value of the yen.
While the markets remain with their siege to the peripheral countries of the EU, the Government of Yoshihiko Noda not lower our guard.
"We must be vigilant to the risks that persist, as the deterioration of some foreign economies, the impact of the floods in Thailand, and the rapid appreciation of the yen," said yesterday, the Secretary of State for Economic Policy, Motohisa Furukawa.
And, indeed, the prospects are not encouraging.
The Organisation for Economic Cooperation and Development (OECD) said that the majority of the Member countries presented in September more visible signs of economic slowdown.
The indicator that anticipates the turning points in the global economy showed that the major powers are slowing down.
Since it fell four tenths to 100.4 points, compared to $100.8 in August.
The euro zone, even, stood below average, which is at the level of 100, the rush to the eight tenths 99.13 points.
Athens is to feed doubts
Papadimos said that it will approve the adjustments, but the Conservatives do not sign any written commitment
With risk premia peripheral fired and uncertainty reinstated in the wooden floors, Greece is still stumbling into the maze that leads towards the exit of the great European debt crisis.
The feeling that the "consensus" of the new transitional government Helleno comes more imposed by the demands of Brussels for a genuine conviction of political forces begins to be confirmed with facts.
While the new prime minister, Lukas Papadimos, warned yesterday that there is no alternative to the structural reforms and that the period of 100 days agreed on his appointment may fall short to implement them, the leader of the conservative New Democracy party, Antonis Samaras, claimed that will not support new austerity measures in any case and reiterated its call for new elections for the scheduled date, on 19 February.
"The main task of this government is to implement the decisions of the summit on 26 October," asserted Papadimos yesterday by opening a parliamentary debate that will culminate tomorrow with a vote of confidence to the new Executive.
A package with 24 programs to boost employment, the reform of the disciplinary code of officials and new measures against tax evasion will be the first initiatives.
However, the message of Samaras not dispels doubts about his position: "We are committed to help the transitional government, but we have not committed to any more."
The Conservative leader was taking a step further in his pulse to the EU and the IMF, the bodies that should unlock the 8 million that Athens urgently needed, and made it clear that it will give its approval to any letter of commitment to meeting the adjustments.
But the European Commission, escocida even by the impact caused by the referendum órdago Papandreou, reiterated yesterday that his demand is strong: Not released the aid if the new government and the leaders of the main parties helenos does not sign "a written commitment without ambiguity and as soon as possible."
The Economic Affairs spokesman, Amadeu Altafaj, explained that the troika inspectors will return "very soon" to Athens to discuss with the new government, "what is needed to pay for the sixth tranche" of 8 million, although there is no deadline.
The Greek knot still has thread for now.
Mrs Sofia: "Are instruments for progress and hope '
The Queen highlights the place "dominant" of Spain in relation to this type of finances
"Has reached a major place globally in the role of the microfinanzas."
Queen Sofia recalled yesterday that the country has become these last two decades in the second donor in relation to this raises a tool of cooperation, whose "essence" pointed out that lies in being an "instrument for social progress, justice and the hope of a better future for all humanity, based on confidence in the human being."
The Queen opened yesterday the V World Summit of microcredit in Valladolid with the belief that "there is no doubt" that is kind of operations are "absolutely essential" to achieve the Millennium Development Goals set by the United Nations with horizon 2015, and, especially, as anyone who has the goal of halving the volume of people living on less than a dollar a day, with which sets the poverty threshold. "
Spain "is working" to expand the network of beneficiaries' to all corners of the planet, and assumes this task with "responsibility," said Sofia, who waited that initiatives and contributions that originate in the summit, which runs until Thursday, "ensure the creation of new skills and better opportunities for the poorest, and especially for women," main beneficiaries of these loans.
Are "many achievements" and "many of the challenges we face."
The Summit of microcredit arises not only as a forum for discussion, but also as a platform to promote "two basic goals."
Thus, His Majesty explained that it aspires to be the end of 2015,175 millions of poor families who have agreed to these financial services and that 100 million of those homes out of the poverty line in the living.
The momentum in the concept of microcredit in Spain and in the rest of the world "has followed the path that began years ago a pioneer" by Muhammad Yunus, I emphasise Sofia as an "act of justice and due recognition."
And is that described the father of this tool as a "universal idealistic admirable in the cause of the fight against poverty," whose work known for 15 years ago, when the Queen traveled to Bangladesh to learn on the ground its policy of loans.
This experience followed a year later the first World Summit in Washington and other events, such as those held in Côte d'Ivoire in 1999, Canada 2006, and "I saw all the continuing evolution," explained Her Majesty, whose link with this project gave him yesterday described as the "head of family" gathered in Valladolid on the part of the "baquero of the poor."
Finally, the Queen Sofia concluded his speech by encouraging people to participate in the discussion and in the search for solutions to make progress in the fight against poverty.
"Ethical imperative '
The foreign minister, Trinidad Jiménez, warned that the solidarity "is an ethical imperative" for all democratic state.
In this sense, explained that it would be a mistake to link the cooperation with developing countries in times of economic boom, because it is a "permanent obligation."
Jimenéz found that microcredit pose "a serious policy and rigorous dedicated to eradicate poverty," and now "more than ever" the governments of developed countries must work under criteria of solidarity and not let this be a victim of the cuts.
In Spain, the microcredit is "one of the main lines of development cooperation."
For his part, the Secretary of State for International Cooperation, Soraya Rodríguez, applauded the "success" of giving "confidence" people "from whom all the doors"; and the mayor of Valladolid, Francisco Javier León of the Riva, welcomed the present to a city that "opens infected the spirit of solidarity."
The CDU proposes to elect the President by universal suffrage
The first day of the congress of the Christian Democratic Union (CDU), on Monday 14 November, in Leipzig, has passed without major difficulties for Angela Merkel, Chancellor and President of the Christian Democrat party.
Initially had not been included on the agenda for the future of Europe, but the issue was imposed in the autumn, in particular to satisfy the militants who believe that the government's policy is currently too lax with the Greeks and could be in a future with the Italians.
The motion on the Presidency of the European Commission, proposed by the management, it took almost unanimously.
Of the 1,001 delegates, there were only nine votes against and 10 abstentions.
The standing ovation for several minutes to be won, with their speeches, Angela Merkel and, after several hours, Wolfgang Schäuble, the Europhile Finance Minister, will allay any doubt as possible.
The main thrust of the Chancellor, and the motion, are summed up in a slogan: The response to the crisis "is not less Europe, but more Europe."
Not only because Europe is peace, but also because "nine million jobs depend directly on the euro."
For the Chancellor, "the time has come to open way in Europe."
This could result in changes to the Lisbon Treaty to enable strengthen the control of the European Union on the budgetary policies of the countries of the euro zone, although it could also lead to the election of the President of the European Commission by universal suffrage to "give a face to Europe."
In any event, this is one of the proposals of the motion adopted by Congress, clear idea of Wolfgang Schäuble.
Without doubt, it is unlikely that the 27 quickly come to an agreement on this radical change: Britain is hostile to him and the leaders of the CDU seem to know that Nicolas Sarkozy, too.
But the ball is on the ground.
On the other hand, the delegates have rejected by an overwhelming majority the proposal to ponder the weight of each country of the directive of the European Central Bank, depending on the weight of each economy, which obviously would strengthen the weight of Germany.
Eager to calm tempers within his party, the Chancellor has increased the references to Konrad Adenauer and Helmut Kohl, but neither is it has tried to win its conference at the expense of the "small" European countries or distressed countries willing to criticise the arrogant Germany.
Although the motion on Europe devotes a section to the importance of "the Franco-German friendship," Angela Merkel has not-discussed in France.
Except passing.
Recalling that, two centuries ago, there was a bloody battle in Leipzig.
In fact, it was one of the most humiliating defeats for the army of Napoleon.
The incidence of fraud in the sick leave
After the subsidies, the UMP and the government launched an offensive against the sick leave.
Nicolas Sarkozy will be on Tuesday, 15 November in Bordeaux to visit a box responsible for family allowances and give a speech on the subject, as recurring since 2007, the fight against fraud and causing social.
Moreover, to accompany such offensive, that part of the desire to save rigorously, but even so reminiscent of an axis of the right-wing presidential campaign, the majority wants to focus on the sick leave.
First, to implement budget cuts: The government plans to impose on private sector workers a fourth day of absence before they can take the low.
In short, unless there is a specific company, a worker who fall ill would lose four days of pay, that is, a minimum of 15% of their monthly income.
This is a measure that could lift a wave of anger, but that would save $280 million, according to Les Echos.
In addition, would be accompanied by another measure with a more symbolic: Impose officials a day of absence without pay in the event of low labour (so far, they have no shortage, compared to the three days that apply in the private sector).
As we discuss these issues, the majority is put on the table the issue of fraud, this time focused on the abuses of parental leave.
"Will be increased considerably controls and, furthermore, if someone was caught in a fraud, it must reimburse the amounts," warned Xavier Bertrand speaking on RTL on Sunday 13 November.
As in other cases, the effects of the announcement seem slightly disproportionate to the reality of fraud in terms of sick leave.
Indeed, since 2002 is a constant monitoring of this issue and have launched several offensives policies that normally have borne fruit.
The French do not become ill more than in the rest of Europe.
Look at carefully, first of all, the national figures.
According to the French Institute of social security (NCWA), in 2006 were paid more than 237 million in benefits for low labour.
According to the French Institute research and documentation in health economics, subsidies for the low accounted for, in 2008, 5% of health care spending, rising to 11.3 million.
Of this amount, 46% corresponds to maternity and occupational accidents, while 54% is related to the sick leave, a figure that amounts to 6.2 billion.
Consequently, 2.5% of spending on health care.
In 2010, the French have picked up an average of 14.5 days off work, compared with 17.8 in 2009, according to a study by the group Alma Consulting.
An average that, without doubt, hides deviations: Another survey, published in 2007 by the Syrian professional management Monster.com, showed that 75 percent of the French respondents claimed 40,000 employees who had not taken a single day of sick leave.
Another study, in this case the Assurance maladie, indicates that in 2010 the 37% of the sick leave lasted less than 8 days, 22% of between 8 and 14 days, 15% of between 15 days and a month, 15% of between one and three months and 11% were more protracted.
Compared with our European neighbours, French workers are not more likely than in other areas to take sick leave.
A long study conducted in 2010 by two researchers at the CNRS indicated that, between 1994 and 2001, the overall rate of absence from work (both for health reasons and otherwise) ranged in France, between 10% and 11%, compared to 20% and 28% in Denmark, 15% in UK or between 16% and 18% in the Netherlands.
Fraud in the sick leave is not particularly significant in comparison with undeclared work.
Fraud has a fairly limited scope.
The strengthening of the legislation, since 2002, has led to the controls of the sick leave more than 45 days are systematic.
In 2008, 1.5 million inspections, the NCWA found in 13% of the 285,000 made, that short-term casualties were "unjustified or too long," i.e. 37,050 cases.
In the case of the casualties of more than 45 days, subject to regular inspections, it was found that 11% of cases were "properly adapted or unjustified; a figure that, starting as a total of 1.2 million, $132,000.
Consequently, there is a total of 169,000 cases "unjustified" among several millions of workers who caught a sick leave.
Without doubt, a figure insignificant compared with, for example, the black economy.
According to the Member of the UMP Dominique Tian, author of a report on this issue in June, this practice would represent a loss of tax revenue of between 9 and 15 billion a year, or more than the total cost of subsidies for low and, without doubt, considerably more than the fraud in this area.
Papadémos: Greece will have to implement a new plan of adjustment
