A committee of experts says that should be legalized euthanasia and assisted suicide
Canadians live denying the death, according to the report by the Royal Society of Canada
In the area of palliative care, the committee calls for governments, health care institutions and doctors to work together to ensure the best palliative care, and not only in cases of cancer.
The Canadian society living denying the death.
Indeed, only 9% of Canadians are willing to talk with your doctor about the conditions in which they want to die and make provisions to that effect.
This is a formidable of the conclusions of a report by the Royal Society of Canada, with the participation of six experts from various fields, including the ethical, legal and doctor.
This committee recommended the government to amend the Penal Code to allow assisted suicide and euthanasia, when the patient is such an option and has been judged competent to make the decision.
For a start, the experts cited a recent survey by the Economist Intelligence Unit that compared the quality of death in 40 countries around the world.
Although Canada ranks 10th post, the study notes that "medicalisation of death in Canada has created a culture in which people are afraid to address the issue of death."
With medication or not, 77% of Canadians do not have access to palliative care, according to the experts selected by the Royal Society of Canada.
And, despite the fact that the majority of Canadians want to die at home, just 68.6% of them died in hospital.
Overall, the highest rate in this regard the records Quebec, where 86% of deaths occur in the hospital.
With regard to the sensitive issue of euthanasia and assisted suicide, the authors of the report came to conclusions that do not coincide with the stance of the federal government, which has already declared that he does not want to amend the Penal Code in relation to euthanasia and assisted suicide.
However, according to experts, who have also studied the situation in all the countries where such practices have been legalized or do not constitute a criminal offence, there is no evidence that the fact that they are not considered a criminal offense has not led to an abuse of its implementation, i.e., the use of euthanasia or assisted suicide with people not competent or who had not given their consent.
Jocelyn Downie, co-author of the report, said yesterday by teleconference that, on the contrary, we saw more excesses in those countries where there have been legalized euthanasia or assisted suicide.
"Canada is practiced euthanasia, although it is clearly illegal."
"Canada is assisted suicide, although it is clearly illegal," explains Jocelyn Downie.
The Canadians, pro-euthanasia
Let us remember that 85 percent of Canadians have already spoken out in favour of euthanasia, because they believe that would allow people whose death is next to alleviate their suffering, according to a survey by Angus Reid made in 2010.
In addition, 66% believes that the fact legalise euthanasia will not to understand that the life of the elderly or disabled has less value.
To the people who have been assisted suicide, 41% of respondents believed that should not begin proceedings against them.
In connection with the maintenance or interruption of health care to a patient, the situation is not so clear, according to the authors of the report.
Moreover, among its recommendations suggest that in the penal code indicating that the withdrawal of health care, if they have rejected legally, it is not a criminal offence.
The committee of experts also calls for training for health professionals in the duty to respect the fact that a patient will reject the attendance at the end of their lives without fear to deal with a complaint.
In the area of palliative care, the committee calls for governments, health care institutions and doctors to work together to ensure the best palliative care, and not only in cases of cancer.
Finally, in relation to the palliative sedation or terminal, which is already used widely in health institutions in Canada, the committee calls that, except that will serve to reduce the physical pain, is seen as euthanasia and be subject to the same procedures.
Other experts expressed reservations
Other experts in the field of health law have already expressed reservations in relation to the conclusions of the report by experts from the Royal Society of Canada.
Pierre Deschamps, a specialist in health law, has described as "extreme" the position of the experts who signed the report, among other things because it restricts the practice of euthanasia to the terminally ill.
"This leaves the door open to a situation in which someone who is tired of living and has more than 18 years can ask for help to commit suicide," said Deschamps, who consulted a summary of the report yesterday.
Mr Deschamps also stresses that the authors of the report seem to give priority to the personal autonomy on any other value of society.
However, it adds that "in society, there are labels and limitations."
The health law specialist in Margaret Somerville also expressed its "strong opposition" with regard to the conclusions of the report, which described as "manifesto in favour of euthanasia."
Margaret Somerville, who also belongs to the Royal Society of Canada, calls into question the lack of abuse, especially in certain countries where euthanasia and assisted suicide is legal, as in the Netherlands and Oregon.
