A Russian scientist has collaborated with the Iranian nuclear programme
A Russian scientist, Vycheslav Danilenko, has worked with Iran in the development of a detonator that can be used in a nuclear weapon, according to said on Monday, an American NGO specialising in the nuclear risk.
For the identification of the investigator, the Institute for Science and International Security (ISIS) is based on a recent report by the International Atomic Energy Agency (IAEA) and in other documents issued by the agency of the UN.
IAEA last week expressed its "grave concern" for a "possible military dimension" of the Iranian nuclear programme.
According to ISIS, based in detail in documents of the IAEA, Danilenko, born in 1934, would have worked for three decades, since the 1960's, in a Soviet military nuclear facility in Tcheliabinsk (Oural) and would have been involved in the manufacture of synthetic diamonds by explosion.
In 1989 and 1991, would have left the center to form a company focused on the production of "nanodiamantes" in Kiev.
The economic problems of their company would have led to contact in 1995, with the Iranian Embassy in Ukraine.
Later, it is believed that cooperated with the Iranian programme between 1996 and 2002, before returning to Russia.
In its latest report, the IAEA says that there are "clear indications that Iran is developing" a nuclear detonation system "with the help of an expert abroad, which not only knew well the technique, but also, as reported by a Member State to the Agency, worked for most of his career in this technology in the military nuclear programme of their country of origin."
The crimes and crimes against Muslims have risen by 50%
The crimes and crimes against Muslims have risen nearly 50% between 2009 and 2010, while, in the same period, the other types of racial and religious violence have decreased or increased only slightly, according to statistics published by the FBI on Monday.
According to those figures, the total number of acts of violence committed against Muslims has gone from 107 in 2009 to 160 in 2010, i.e., has risen by 49%, compared to an increase of 13% in the case of acts of violence against Catholics, a reduction of 4 percent in crimes against Jews and an overall increase of 14% in the number of crimes and offences anti-religious.
The total number of "hate crimes" has grown slightly until the 6,628 cases, of whom a 47.3 percent is due to racial differences and 20% to religious differences, according to the FBI.
"After a decline in 2009, it is worrying that have risen again this type of crimes and offences," stressed the human rights organisation Human Rights First, "the increase in acts of violence against Muslims is particularly significant," the organisation added in a statement.
"Human Rights First has long been pointing out that violence against Muslims, as well as all types of hate crimes, should be considered as a serious violation of human rights," adds a responsible for the organisation, Paul Legendre.
"The US government can and must strive to put an end to these abuses," adds, given that such efforts could include an improvement of police reports on the "hate crimes".
"Hate crime" in the US federal law is inherited from the era of the struggle for civil rights.
This legislation was adopted after the death of Martin Luther King to punish acts of violence linked to the race, color, religion, descent and, now, the sexual orientation.
