Austria,
Introduction of a "golden rule" in the Constitution budget
The grand coalition Government of Social Democrat/Christian Democrat who is in power in Austria has decided on Tuesday to include in the Constitution a "golden rule" budget to reduce the public deficit and thus avoid a possible deterioration of the sovereign note of Austria by rating agencies (triple-A).
It was the Social Democratic Chancellor Werner Faymann, who announced the decision following a Council of Ministers, when the Austrian public debt reached 74.6%, a figure well above the upper limit of 60% set by the Maastricht Treaty, but clearly inferior to the debts of countries such as Italy, Greece or Spain.
"If you reduce the solvency of Austria in a single level, from AAA to AA +, we would have to pay $3 million more in interest each year," said the Christian Democrat Deputy Minister of Foreign Affairs, Michael Spindelegger.
Austria responds to a request from the Brussels summit to member countries of the eurozone last 26.10.98: In it, the Heads of State and Government called for the inclusion, before the end of 2012, the reduction of the public deficit and the recovery of the balance of public accounts in the Constitution or an Act equivalent value.
The measures adopted by the Austrian Government is close to the "German model", as Germany was the first European country that took that kind of "rule."
By 2017, the structural budget deficit should decrease each year in a 0.75 percent of gross domestic product (GDP) and, from 2017, the federal government's structural budget deficit should not exceed each year 0.35% of GDP, while the regional states, as well as the communes, should submit balanced budgets.
The aim is that, by 2020/2021, public debt will be reduced under the criterion of 60% set by the Maastricht Treaty.
