Energy policy:
Facts must assert more than the dogmas
If there is an issue that cannot be dealt with considerations of short-term or simply thinking about emotions, is energy policy.
The availability and cost of electricity directly influence the purchasing power and the competitiveness of businesses.
It is appropriate that an electoral meeting is the time to reflect on these issues and on the place of nuclear energy.
The debate will be useful only if studying all the economic, social and environmental consequences of the proposed options.
The French must base its opinion on objective facts, rational data.
Now that we are 7 billion people on the planet, demographic trends will result in the doubling of demand for electricity by 2050 unless it deprives a huge part of the world's population of a vital element.
At the same time, we will have to alleviate the increasing scarcity of fossil resources to continue producing electricity continuously, without forgetting the urgent need to reduce greenhouse gas emissions to combat climate change, an issue that has disappeared from the environmental debate.
The Fukushima does not change any of these parameters.
Therefore, Germany remains alone in its decision to abandon nuclear power.
This is not the case or Belgium, which makes its way to the need to find a source able to replace it, nor of Switzerland, which only aims to build power plants in the last generation.
On the other hand, Britain, Finland, Poland, the Czech Republic, the Netherlands, Sweden, South Africa, China, India and Brazil, for example, are forward with determination with their projects.
The United States, by his side, after Fukushima decided to add a unit to the park, picking up the construction of a plant suspended after the accident at Three Mile Island.
If the German model, based on renewable energy, is sometimes as an example, the reality is against such a speech.
The choice of Berlin will lead to a rise in the price of electricity, greater energy dependence on imported gas increased the need, in particular Russia, an increase of CO2 emissions for the construction of gas and coal plants.
In a few months, will be felt the harmful effects.
We must think about the case of Denmark.
European champion in the wind industry, which gets 30% of its electricity, it is also one of the biggest users of coal and gas due to the wind intermittency; for this reason, their CO2 emissions and the price of its electricity are, respectively, a 65% and 50% higher than the European average.
On the contrary, thanks to the record of our energy policy, our neighbours paid an electricity bill 40% higher than the French households.
While in a globalized economy, the cost of energy is a key factor in the competitiveness and a guarantee of the maintenance of the utility industry in the national territory, French companies benefit from cheaper electricity in Europe.
For this reason, any significant reduction of nuclear energy would be a sharp rise in the price of electricity, which would realism to the wonderful statements on the reindustrialization of our country and the defence of our purchasing power.
It is a price that the vast majority of the French are refusing to pay and, in fact, are not opposed in principle to this type of energy, polls show.
Remember that the energy policy of our country has lost to build an industrial sector with 125,000 jobs director and 410,000 indirect jobs.
Largely export-oriented, covers a galaxy of small and medium-sized enterprises specializing in international markets and non-relocatable that can create jobs.
If France decided to abandon nuclear energy, would be the sacrifice of a large part of these SMEs and the loss of $6 million annually in French exports of nuclear equipment and services.
What would an electrician EPR designed to operate 60 years, when it is expected the collapse of its manufacturer?
To solve the equation of nuclear energy, we must admit that there is no miracle source of electricity production, as there is a diabolical source.
The development by Areva of solutions with low CO2 emissions, nuclear and renewable, shows the complementary nature of energy sources.
In the case of nuclear energy, it is essential to maintain the highest level of security.
In France, we have a security authority that exerts tight control and transparent on both existing plants and the construction of Flamanville.
Our teams, recognized professionalism, are also obsessed with security.
In half a century, the nuclear sector has suffered three serious accidents.
Just one, the Three Mile Island, occurred in normal operating conditions; not provocó consequences or to people or the environment.
In Chernobyl, the accident was due to the design of the reactor and a human error unforgivable.
Fukushima, some people seem to forget that the accident was due to two natural disasters of unprecedented scope, which resulted in the deaths of tens of thousands of people.
The nuclear sector will learn from this accident, as it did in the previous two.
Thanks to this progress and cooperation between the security authorities and the French and German operators and manufacturers, the EPR design presents a capable of resisting such phenomena.
While the study all the players who want to build an electric power station, the termination of its construction in Flamanville would be a great gift to competitors from Areva and EDF, because that would leave them a free hand to take the lead in the inevitable development of the nuclear sector.
It is essential and legitimate to seek the best energy options for our country, but it would be irresponsible to let the emotion, dogmas and they have a command partisan maneuvering such an important debate for the economic, social and financial situation of our country.
Immigration, is a burden or an opportunity for the economy?
Immigration policy implemented by Nicolas Sarkozy has been criticized from various points of view: The saturation of the police services, judicial and administrative subjected to the policy of figures, the compatibility of this policy with self-proclaimed the status of "country of human rights" of France.
More recently, is the administrative harassment of foreign students who jumped to the headlines, with the Ministry of Interior (see the newspaper Libération on 23 May) proclaiming of past that France "does not need foreign talent, workers or waiters."
However, rarely discusses from an economic point of view.
The point is that, on this issue, there is quite a consensus between the left and the right.
In the case of the right, Jacques Chirac set the direction in 1976, declaring that "900,000 unemployed should not be a problem for a country with nearly two million migrant workers," while on the left, the tone was set by Michel Rocard explaining that France "cannot take care of all the misery of the world" in 1990.
The only difference, the degree of generosity
In 2005, both left and right shared the fear of invasion of the national territory for a multitude of Polish plumbers.
On both sides, it considers that immigrants are a burden for the French economy and society.
The only difference is in the extent of generosity with which act with regard to immigrants.
In its programme, François Hollande is limited to include trivia, indicating that the co-development will solve the problem of migration. "
This idea of immigration as a burden, a problem, perhaps it is profitable electorally, but economically is very expensive.
As economists point Ian Goldin, Geoffrey Cameron in a recent book that sums up the latest knowledge on immigration (Exceptional People: How Migration Shaped Our World and Will defines Our Future, May 2011, Princeton University Press; 352 PP.), there is a broad consensus among experts on the positive impact of migration flows in economic growth, wages and employment in the countries that receive immigrants.
Limiting immigration weakens growth and is detrimental to employment.
The fears related to the impact of immigrants are based on the idea that these can replace national workers, particularly the low-skilled, pushing to reduce their salaries.
But experience shows that, in reality, immigrants are complementary rather than substitutes for national workers and are mainly professions in sectors with lack of employment.
Low-skilled immigrants working in sectors that do not attract national and the most skilled workers in dynamic sectors where the training does not meet the demand for staff.
A positive effect on wages
In the same way that a surgeon would find it difficult to work in a country that has a lack of anaesthetists, complementarity between citizens and immigrants causes the arrival of recent will impact positively on wages and employment of nationals.
Taking into account the above, Giovanni peri calculated that a 1% increase in migratory flows is a rise in real wages in the long term of between 0.6 and 0.9%.
And, without taking into account the fact that the diversity that provide immigrants contributes to creating ideas and economic growth (there is a large proportion of Nobel laureates and naturalized American companies such as Google, Intel, PayPal, eBay and Yahoo were founded by immigrants).
Immigrants also are net contributors to the social systems, because they provide an average of 1% of the total budget in European countries.
The International Labour Organisation estimates, for example, that in Germany, an immigrant who arrives with an age of 30 years will make a net contribution (revenue less costs) of 150,000 euros in public budgets on average throughout his life.
At the beginning of his mandate, Nicolas Sarkozy wanted to go to seek the points of growth that he lacked "with teeth."
These teeth, which discouraged immigrants, had exactly the opposite effect.
Europe invented democracy, you only need to think in a European democracy
Democracy is a valuable asset, but also fragile.
The European continent should be able to remember it because, although it was invented in Athens over two thousand years ago, during the 20th century has suffered the tragedies of the World War, totalitarianism, the Holocaust, the gulag, but also to Franco in Spain, Salazar in Portugal, the colonels in Greece.
Some may have believed that, for democracy triunfase definitely on their enemies, would be enough to vote and the most direct way possible.
We know, since Napoleon "Little," that it was something thought.
Universal suffrage, although it is a necessary condition for democracy, is not enough on its own and even can become an instrument of oppression, "as the philosopher Etienne Vacherot formerly Republican.
No, democracy requires much more: A public space, a public spirit, values, an organization, a separation of powers and control, an education, lights, economic and social solidarity, justice.
The crisis that we live in Europe is an economic crisis, but is on the verge of becoming a political crisis and democratic.
The Greek referendum palinodia of true-false had, in this regard, revealing a double effect: Showed the need for a strong return to the political sphere, but also the worrying sense of its failure, his inconsistency.
Must consider this ambivalence to overcome it.
The truth is that the front lines of the battle democrática have now been moved and, in many cases, soldiers Republicans no longer are moving in the right direction.
Stands to gain if not demand a succession of national referendums, organized around the needs and disorderly manner.
A blank cheque to the European monarch absolute or a high into the void of the nationalist hole: What options for the citizen!
No, we do not want to coups, but a joint exercise, fully-fledged, calm and steady, options and democracy, this time at European level.
There is no crisis in Greece, Italy, Spain, Portugal (in fact, we would have no idea where to end the list), because there is only a crisis, the crisis in Europe.
The whole of Europe is that it is bowing to the orders of the markets and rating agencies, which suffers from its impotence and its lack of solidarity.
It is the whole of Europe suffers a humiliation in the international arena.
We worry about the transfer of sovereignty to Europe, but all Europe is slowly losing the sovereignty and, with it, every one of their nations.
The most urgent is that popular sovereignty to regain the helm of the European project.
Because it is only together can Europeans to reduce the weight of its debts, free markets and prepare for their future through investments.
The exit from the crisis will require decisions at European level that may not be taken without a full democratic legitimacy, unless it is to lead to disaster.
Having fought for a long time against this proposal of the socialists and Jacques Delors, everyone calls today a European economic governance.
That it.
But think about it without further political integration and democratic, and without being seen as such by the citizens, it would be a new madness and would lead us to a new deadlock.
We must take a new stage of European integration.
To build the Republic in France, it was necessary to "do" Republicans.
The Revolution motivated by interests would not be enough.
This lesson remains applicable.
Need to build a more integrated Europe from an economic point of view.
It can only be achieved by building a more democratic Europe at the political level, a real European popular sovereignty.
To build Europe, do Europeans.
Chip cards with "no contact" is widespread
Lounge global chip cards began on Tuesday in Villepinte, near Paris, with an environment optimistic.
Indeed, the year 2011 should end with an 11% increase in global sales of cards with microprocessors (bank cards, telephone SIM card, etc.), with a total of 6 million units, according to calculations Eurosmart cabinet.
The segment is the most powerful technology without contact, which allows us to pay the transport in common purchases or simply approaching the card at a reader.
This year will be sold worldwide 460 million cards with chip without contact, 320 million more than the previous year.
Should continue to increase its share in 2012 (includes 580 million units) and represent nearly 10% of the global market for cards with chip cards (6,925 million).
Europe, which has long been behind the Asia-Pacific region, is gaining ground in the area of payment without contact.
Around 26 million bank cards Visa already have this function, which is accepted in 75,000 payment terminals.
In France, its beginnings are more modest: They are using 400,000 Visa cards without contact.
But the supermarkets are working for four.
Carrefour has issued this year 2.5 million cards Pass MasterCard without contact.
To get the gear, however, it is necessary for banks to make them available to its customers.
"There are two major French establishments that have been undertaken to disseminate systematically in the future, among its customers, bank cards without contact with the system," announces Gérard Nébouy, director-general of Visa Europe France.
Banks tested the payment for mobile phone
But it is only a first step towards the means of payment of the future: The mobile phone.
At present, there are few devices equipped with the technology NFC (near Field Communication), essential to make transactions.
"Are falling behind."
"But should finally see a real boom next year."
"We anticipate that it will sell between 80 and 120 million units in 2012 throughout the world," explains Marc Bertin, chairman of Eurosmart.
But banks take the lead.
The bank Crédit agricole yesterday announced the launch of a test between December and next June in Caen.
The iPhone are equipped to around 200 customers and partners with a sheath that allows the payment without contact.
The BPCE has a similar project in Strasbourg and Marseille.
And the Société générale also said yesterday that he is preparing the marketing of an offer to allow their customers pay without contact via their mobile.
The Sahara to Nigeria, the terrorist front is on the rise
Paris is concerned about the links between al-Qaeda in the Islamic Maghreb and the Boko Haram sect.
The links between the terrorist group al-Qaeda in the Islamic Maghreb (AQIM) and the Nigerian sect Boko Haram, on which they suspected for some time, have been confirmed.
On Sunday, the Algerian Minister of Foreign Affairs, Abdelkader Messahel, even said that Algiers already "has the certainty."
"The way in which both organizations operate and the intelligence reports show that they are cooperating," explained, without providing further details.
Paris seems to come to a similar conclusion.
The investigation into the abduction of two Frenchmen in Niger last January would have resumed the gateways.
Abducted in a restaurant in Niamey by people associated with AQIM, Antoine de Léocour and Vincent Delory died the next day along with several of his kidnappers during an operation launched by French special forces.
In the rubble of the intervention, French researchers discovered several Nigerian and telephone chips that belonged to the terrorists.
Of terrorist axis
The study of calls made indicates to several players based in Mali, Niger and Nigeria.
According to Radio France Internationale (RFI), two numbers attracted the interest of researchers: One leads to a Nigerian who remained for a long time in Maiduguri, a city in northern Nigeria, cradle of Boko Haram, and the other to a man who, presumably, is close to AQIM and the sect.
"This is progress, but certainly we should expect to have more formal evidence before talk of operational cooperation between Boko Haram and AQIM."
"But it is possible."
"We have known for years that the sect enjoys foreign financial support and intellectual and that is increasingly active," says Kunle Amuwo, a Nigerian researcher.
In recent months, these "support" had been increasingly evident in the evolution and the speeches of Boko Haram or in their operational modes, which now involve the use of suicide bombers or explosive devices increasingly complex, and in the same style than those used by AQIM.
The international community, starting with Washington is pressuring Abudja since then to take into account the problems generated by Boko Haram.
The Nigerian authorities, in fact, have long been considering the group as a community of enlightened little worthy of interest.
A success fast
Founded in 2002 in Maiduguri around a mosque, a school and the fundamentalist imam Mohammed Yusuf, Boko Haram (which means, in Hausa, "Western education is a sin"), encourages the establishment of an Islamic emirate in the Muslim north of Nigeria.
In this poor region, the association is experiencing a quick success.
Be politicized and requires a strict observance of Sharia law, while its militants launched the fight against the central government godless.
These are the first to churches, pubs, administrations.
In 2009, Boko Haram militants were particularly active and multiplied attacks on police stations.
The Abudja reaction was, as so often happens, widespread.
The army attacked the town and there were 800 deaths.
Mohammed Yusuf, arrested in life, receives the death in prison.
Since then, the sect is radicalizing and abandoned their fiefdoms in the north.
Last Christmas, calls for an attack that causes 80 dead in Jos and, later, another in Abuja.
In June, Boko Haram returns to attack against Muscat, particularly against the headquarters protected by the police, with a suicide attack, the first of its kind.
In August, the local headquarters of the United Nations becomes his first international goal.
The creation of an axis of terrorism in Africa, which would cover from Mauritania to Somalia from Nigeria, anxious to all security specialists.
While AQIM has attacked Mali and Niger and the Somali Al-Chebab operate in Kenya, Boko Haram emerges as a new threat in the centre of the continent.
Last week, during a meeting in Nigeria with President Goodluck Jonathan, Alain Juppé has warned against Boko Haram and said he was willing to "share all the information."
The world according to the Republican candidates for the Presidency
In relation to China, with Iran and with the aid to Israel, Mitt Romney, Herman presidential and Rick Perry vie in naivety and lack of knowledge.
An America weakened by the crisis, can manage a complex world with simple ideas, or even simplistic?
Listening to the Republican candidates for the presidential elections, voters might think that is the case.
A few days ago, Mitt Romney, Herman presidential, Rick Perry and the other candidates are becoming more statements estruendosas and shortcuts in terms of foreign policy, traditionally a strong point of Republicans.
Extend the slogans, often infundamentados, on China, Iran, aid to Israel.
Mitt Romney, the candidate best placed in the race for the nomination for the "Grand Old Party", has threatened to take China to the WTO and denouncing them "by manipulating its currency," a key issue in an America exasperated by the migration of entire fragments of their sector towards Asia.
As if that means the explosion of a trade war, he said.
Jon Huntsman, former Ambassador of Obama in China and the only candidate who has a sophisticated vision of foreign policy, almost drown before an attitude that "apabulla 'emotions.
Has called for a dialogue, but constructive, with Beijing (the current position of Obama).
But Huntsman, which is stalled in the depths of the opinion polls, remains inaudible.
Reagan-style
Romney has also promised a military intervention in Iran if sanctions fail to halt its nuclear program.
"If re-elected, will stop Iran," fanfarroneó.
"If Obama gets re-elected, they will have the bomb."
Also promised to increase military aid to Israel, accusing Obama of having failed in its obligations in connection with this partner.
The businessman Herman Cain, the second candidate best classified, shows for its part a shameful lack of such issues.
Recently, urged to counter the military threat of China because Beijing "is trying to develop nuclear capability", apparently ignoring the fact that China already has the military atom since 1964.
The Texan, Mr Governor Rick Perry, who supports Israel and wants to intervene in Iran, says that, for its part, is ready to deploy the US military in Mexico to combat the drug cartels.
The use of torture against suspected terrorists banned by Obama in 2009, will also recommend Cain, Perry and the candidate Michele Bachmann.
There are considerable differences with the Republican nominee in 2008, John McCain, a heavyweight in foreign policy.
Opponents of the current President Reagan answered that also had a simple ideas and who won the Cold War.
Recall that Obama himself was an amateur and had to loosen the piston in the fight against terrorism.
Insist, with reason, in the failure of his naive dialogue with Iran, in the hasty exit from the "boys" of Iraq and its distortions in Libya, and labeled as weak.
But the attacks are not simple.
The population is of a more positive assessment of Obama's national security, which ended with bin Laden.
In Iraq, is wary of military interventions that generate a collapse.
And, arguing that we need to rebuild America economically to resurrect his leadership, Obama gives the impression of being more fair.
The Nord Stream, new gateway of Russian gas in Europe
The Nord Stream pipeline, which connects directly Western Europe with Russia through the bottom of the Baltic Sea, has already been put into service.
To supply gas to meet the needs of 30 million homes.
Gazprom, the Russian gas giant, has wanted to celebrate the event with great pomp.
Last Tuesday, more than 500 guests, including four Heads of State and Government, participated on the shores of the Baltic, between the music of the orchestra and a delicate bufet, at the opening of the Nord Stream, the new pipeline that connects directly under the sea, Russia with Germany.
Symbolically, German Chancellor Angela Merkel, Russian President Dmitry Medvedev, French Prime Minister François Fillon and his counterpart in the Netherlands, Mark Rutte, have been together the wheel of the valve that controls the entry of Russian gas in the network of Western Europe.
With this new pipeline, will each year 27.5 billion cubic metres of Russian gas to Western Europe via a first had to 1,224 km connecting the region of St. Petersburg with the Land of Mecklenburg-Pomerania.
A second tube should be concluded by the end of 2012, which will provide a total of 55 billion cubic metres of gas, that is to say, enough to cover the entire French consumption.
Moreover, there is already talk of the possibility of building a third tube for the same way.
For Gazprom, the timely completion of this huge project presents an air of victory.
Poland and the Baltic countries had been firmly opposed to the project.
Indeed, Nord Stream will allow supplying gas directly to Germany, avoiding the course land for third countries (Poland and Ukraine).
In one fell swoop, these two countries are losing some of its power: For them, it will be more difficult to influence Russia threatened to block access to the markets of Western Europe.
At the height of the debate, Warsaw has not hesitated to compare the Nord Stream as a "new German-Soviet pact," in reference to the alliance between Hitler and Stalin to occupy Poland in 1939.
Is, if the issue is politically sensitive.
Western Europe, supporting the Russian draft, has gained greater security of supply.
But the price is a weakening of the Europe of energy, given that the project has created a rift between the Eastern and Western Europe.
Russia has known, in just five years, to succeed his vision of a direct alliance between Russia and Western countries rich, big consumers of gas reserves and increasingly limited.
"This pipeline is a component of our partnership with Russia, a new artery that unites us of organically," confirmed François Fillon during the inauguration of the pipeline, showing the extent to which the big gas contracts are as political as well as economic.
All this explains the broad smiles on the faces of the managers of Gazprom, many in Lubmin, at the point of arrival of the gas.
The construction of this pipeline is also a technical achievement.
The submarine is made of steel tube cement covered to protect it against the anchors of ships.
Rests on the bottom of the sea, to an average of 200 metres deep.
To build it, it was necessary to avoid minefields dating from the Second World War.
"It was necessary to remove or destroy a hundred of them, for caution," says Jens Müller, spokesman for the Nord Stream society.
Also became necessary step up measures to protect the flora and fauna.
The tube is a long snake of metal that weighs as 242 Eiffel Towers and is not interrupted along its entire length: Or valves, or maintenance stations.
Scheduled a platform of control in the waters of Sweden, but those responsible for the project renounced the same to see that the Swedes were not very willing to allow a Russian state society was permanently in the sea off its shores.
"In case of breakdown, we will interrupt the passage of gas in less than a minute," said Jens Müller.
In the event of a leak, the gas pipeline will be released to the atmosphere.
But the builders considered unlikely that there will be a leak, because they have planned gaskets, according to forecasts, will have a flight per 100,000 years.
Control of the state of the pipeline is guaranteed by a robot submarine, dragged by a ship, which is carrying out external inspections, as well as through a device that circulates in the interior of the pipeline.
With the shape of a cigar, introduced inside the tube, which has a diameter of a metre, and moves with gas.
Upon arrival, after three full days of travel at a speed of three metres per second, provides accurate data on potential deformations of the metal.
The pipeline has been designed to operate for 50 years without the need for any kind of redress.
The movement of the gas is simply because of the pressure.
The principle is 200 bars and, at the exit of 100 bars.
Five companies have joined forces to be able to carry out this project.
The company is leader Gazprom, which owns 51 percent of the shares.
To her, joined the German E.ON and BASF (15.5% each), as well as the Dutch Gasunie and the French group GDF Suez (9% each).
These five companies have created a joint venture, called Nord Stream to build and operate the pipeline.
It has its headquarters in Zug, Switzerland, where the imposition is particularly favourable.
Later, Gazprom rented to this society, for a renewable term of 25 years, all the gas transport capabilities.
"Gazprom will pay for the total capacity, regardless of the amount of gas that is really transport," said Jens Müller.
Funding for the construction of the pipeline has been carried out by 30% with the input of shareholders and 70% through bank loans.
The total cost of the project should reach 7.4 million for the two tubes.
For GDF Suez, for example, investment has reached the 240 million.
But minority shareholders are sure that does not exceed their investment, because Gazprom alone assumes the risk of expenses.
Baltic emerges the pipeline in Lubmin, in a sandy coast planted pine.
Some valves, with 4.5 metres high, form the exit door of gas.
There are a few sensors that measure the pressure, the temperature and the specific characteristics of the gas on arrival, before being transferred to the German pipelines.
Since last Tuesday, the terminal receives a million cubic metres of Russian gas every hour.
At full capacity, will be three million per hour and in 2012, six million.
Moleskine, a report card.
Created a half-century ago by an Italian company, Moleskine wants to give people a taste for the script.
Has an air of adventure, hours of writing to light a candle.
The Moleskine notebook is easily recognized, with its black rectangular pasta, his gum, their white sheets broke, as aging at the time.
However, the Moleskine notebooks with the current side were born... in 1997.
The Italian company Mode Mode, based in Milan, decided at that time to market a notebook of design, but distinguished.
Maria Mr. Sebregondi, then a consultant to the company, saw the launch of the new product.
The book was inspired by an ancient technique of production, though the skinheads (skin of mole), which refers to a cotton barnizado that was used, among other things, to cover the stools.
This kind of book was highly valued by the writers and travellers.
"Moleskine has adapted to the current taste an object old and forgotten, an icon of the pioneering artists until the 20th century," Maria Sebregondi account, which since then became responsible for the brand in Mode Mode.
And reached the success.
Between 2006 and 2010, sales rose by 26%, reaching a volume of 12.7 million units sold.
Far remained confidential production of the first few years, in which only 3,000 books were designed.
Moleskine goes beyond the borders of Italy and exported their products in 70 countries, from France to the United States.
It is difficult to determine the profile of the buyer, since the notebook attracts both businessmen and students and professionals.
Like Moleskine, its users are cosmopolitan, open-mindedness and cults.
The small Italian company, which had 12 workers in its infancy, now owns nearly 100 and, since 2008, has two offices: One in Milan and the other in New York.
Distributes its basis in bookshops, from the FNAC until small shops in the centre of the cities, and has managed to impose its identity.
"We have adapted to the times and the need to write, despite the rise of e-mails," explains Maria Mr. Sebregondi.
This signature cultural goes hand in hand with the development of Moleskine: Recently, the brand has launched the exhibition "Detour" where architects and artists out his own book.
In August, also launched a notebook with lids of leopard, on the occasion of the Locarno Film Festival.
Taking advantage of its success and this aura cultural, Moleskine has managed to diversify their products: Handbags, agendas, pens, computer blankets... The marks covers a wide range of media.
A success that causes envy: In the autumn of 2006, Mode Mode was acquired by the investment fund GS Capital Europe, currently Syntegra Capital, written a new page in the history of Moleskine.
Why the unemployment rate for disabled workers remains so high?
About 19% of disabled people are looking for a job.
The 15th Week for the employment of the disabled begins today.
Despite a resolute public policy, implemented since 2005, the unemployment rate among the disabled is twice the average rate: 19%, compared to 9% for the whole population.
How daunting?
"No," says Éric Blanchet, director general of Adapt, the association that organises the week for the employment of the disabled.
"The progress made since 15 years ago are considerable.
"At that time, the unemployment rate was not twice, but three times higher than the average.
"However, there is still much to be done."
It is worth mentioning that the unemployed disabled still face numerous obstacles to access to employment.
They tend to have an older age: 37% has more than 50 years (17% on average).
Have a little high level of qualification: 80% has not finished high school, and of the 2.3 million students in higher education, only 10,000 are disabled.
Finally, long-term unemployment is rife among them: 53% for the disabled, compared to 38% on average.
That is to say, there are many issues that impede the return to the world of work and that "are the crux of the problem," says Christian Grapin, director-general of Tremplin, a partnership founded in 1992 to help businesses to hire disabled workers.
These are the obstacles.
In addition, there are those who have not been mentioned; the mentality of the people moving, but too slowly.
A study carried out in April by the association for the IMS-entreprendre Cité indicated that the directors surveyed have "a level of knowledge on disability under", with an "over-representation of people in wheelchairs, poor physical or intellectuals."
The result: Private companies with more than 20 workers are very far from the goal of hiring a 6% of disabled workers, a goal that was set in a law... 1987.
According to the latest figures available, dating from 2008, reach a ratio of 2.6%.
"Now we reached around 3%," says Pierre Blanc, director-general of Agefiph, the agency responsible for collecting contributions from companies that do not respect the law.
The test: The number of establishment "subjected to this contribution," like the sums disbursed, have fallen between 2007 and 2011, from $59 to $46,000 (and 606 to 480 million euros).
"The law of 2005, which increased contributions, has generated a great deal of pressure for businesses," explains Pierre Blanc.
"But this improvement also reflects a real awareness, especially among the large groups."
According to the Ministry of Labour, only 59% of companies that have between 20 and 49 workers account with disabled employees in its workforce, compared to 82% of companies of between 100 and 199 employees.
Hazard: "A joy '
About to face the bleus Tuesday evening (20h45), Eden Hazard and Georges Leekens do not hide the pleasure that creates this match.
We dare not say that there was collusion between them, but the image is symbolic.
Sitting side by side, on the podium in the auditorium of the Stade de France, Georges Leekens and Eden Hazard really have made amends.
Five months after the gesture of resentment of his striker against Turkey, the Belgian selector has no more than praise for him.
"I was very pleased by Eden, for their progress and Belgian because it is."
"I want to move forward," he responds the striker of Lille.
In terms of the contrast between their presentations in his team and in the selection, "is a whole," has been justified.
"In Lille, I am all year, which does not apply to Belgium.
"I have to put myself."
Convened to play against Romania on Friday night, taking into account this match against France, Hazard comes to Saint-Denis, finally, "shine."
Without forget the "pleasure."
Has been encouraging the bleus since he was seven years, as well as during the victorious campaigns in 1998 and 2000.
"I have always been a fan," says.
Without doubt, this will strengthen the character "particular" of the meeting.
Especially because they face "Mathieu Debuchy, Yohan Cabaye and Adil Rami," recalls.
"We have just face recently.
"Playing against them is always a joy."
With simplicity, Leekens has done its part by reference to "pride".
"Pride" in play "a gala party."
"Pride" also by check, as "a neighbour," France "is becoming a team of very high level," nearly a year after the trauma of Knysna.
"Laurent Blanc has done a tremendous job," he said with enthusiasm.
While Belgium will not attend the next European competition, the technician would be delighted to be able to share with the plane bleus towards... Brazil in 2014.
"Our small Belgians are growing," he stressed.
"We are building something; the players are ambitious, they are hungry.
"To see it in the next few games." Including the match against France.
Portugal shows great confidence
Portugal's Paulo Bento is faced with a great optimism the party back against Bosnia (22h00), which will be held on Tuesday in Lisbon.
In the one-party, lacked realism to both teams.
"When within these 90 minutes, we will be a happy team and, above all, a country happy."
Paulo Bento is already seen in Poland and Ukraine.
There is no doubt; the Selecçao, which runs from September 2010, will qualify for Euro 2012.
Indeed, just 90 minutes separate Portugal of happiness.
But there is a party that play and a rival, Bosnia, that defeat.
Bearing in mind the party trip (0-0), on Friday in the hell of Zenica, it seems clear that the matter is not resolved.
Portugal dominated the party for more than an hour, yes, but could not make the valuable goal that would have given the tranquillity.
"It is a good result, but at the same time, carries a risk, since we have not scored away from home."
But at home, in the bright Stade de la Luz of Lisbon, the Portuguese are convinced that will pass, before an audience that should be just as excited, even if it is clear that the party "is well matched," Bento dixit an optimistic but lucid.
"We hope that the party is well matched, but we are absolutely convinced that we can take the lead," said the Portuguese coach for 42 years.
"We still have a 50% chance of participating in Euro 2012," has, however, put the successor of Carlos Queiroz.
Friday the stalemate in Bosnia obliges the Portuguese to mark and win.
Bosnians they could get a draw, but also need to make.
"It is a good result, but at the same time, carries a risk, because we have not scored away from home," Bento regrets.
"We are going to play against a team that has a great technical quality and we have players with a great individual quality," he added.
As in Zenica, the Portuguese will go with the intention of exercise, from the outset, a maximum pressure on the Bosnians to "do not give them time to think."
A good idea, provided that, this time, is realistic.
